  version: {fileID: 11400000, guid: 51ee3e37f5ded7941ab6216610f6fc67, type: 2}
  description: 'The Book of Genesis is the first book of the Bible, and it contains
    a comprehensive account of the creation of the world, the early history of humanity,
    and the origins of the Israelite people. In the New Living Translation (NLT),
    Genesis is presented with a narrative style that is accessible and easy to understand.
    Here''s a brief overview of the themes and content found in the Book of Genesis:



    1.
    Creation: Genesis begins with the creation of the world by God in six days. This
    includes the formation of the heavens, the earth, plants, animals, and ultimately,
    humans, who are created in the image of God.



    2. Adam and Eve: The book
    introduces the first human beings, Adam and Eve, and narrates their life in the
    Garden of Eden. It also discusses the fall of humanity through disobedience,
    leading to the introduction of sin and its consequences.



    3. Noah and the
    Flood: Genesis recounts the story of Noah, who is chosen by God to build an ark
    to save himself, his family, and a pair of each kind of animal from a worldwide
    flood.



    4. The Patriarchs: The book traces the lives of key figures, including
    Abraham, Isaac, and Jacob (Israel), highlighting their relationships with God,
    the establishment of the covenant, and the promises made to them.



    5. Joseph''s
    Story: Genesis concludes with the story of Joseph, one of Jacob''s sons, who
    becomes a powerful figure in Egypt. The narrative describes his journey from
    being sold into slavery by his brothers to becoming a high-ranking official.



    Overall,
    Genesis sets the foundation for the entire biblical narrative, exploring themes
    of creation, sin, redemption, and the establishment of God''s covenant with humanity.
    It provides crucial context for understanding the subsequent books of the Bible.'
  chapters:
  - verses:
    - title: The Account of Creation
      content: '  In the beginning God created the heavens and the earth.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:1 '
        content: Or <b>In the beginning when God created the heavens and the earth,
          . . . </b>Or <b>When God began to create the heavens and the earth, . .
          .</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The earth was formless and empty, and darkness covered the deep waters.
        And the Spirit of God was hovering over the surface of the waters.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet there be light,\u201D and there was light. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And God saw that the light was good. Then he separated the light
        from the darkness. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God called the light \u201Cday\u201D and the darkness \u201Cnight.\u201DAnd
        evening passed and morning came, marking the first day.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet there be a space between the waters, to
        separate the waters of the heavens from the waters of the earth.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And that is what happened. God made this space to separate the waters
        of the earth from the waters of the heavens. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God called the space \u201Csky.\u201DAnd evening passed and morning
        came, marking the second day.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet the waters beneath the sky flow together
        into one place, so dry ground may appear.\u201D And that is what happened. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God called the dry ground \u201Cland\u201D and the waters \u201Cseas.\u201D
        And God saw that it was good. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet the land sprout with vegetation\u2014every
        sort of seed-bearing plant, and trees that grow seed-bearing fruit. These
        seeds will then produce the kinds of plants and trees from which they came.\u201D
        And that is what happened. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The land produced vegetation\u2014all sorts of seed-bearing plants,
        and trees with seed-bearing fruit. Their seeds produced plants and trees
        of the same kind. And God saw that it was good.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And evening passed and morning came, marking the third day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet lights appear in the sky to separate the
        day from the night. Let them be signs to mark the seasons, days, and years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let these lights in the sky shine down on the earth.\u201D And that
        is what happened. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God made two great lights\u2014the larger one to govern the day,
        and the smaller one to govern the night. He also made the stars. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'God set these lights in the sky to light the earth, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'to govern the day and night, and to separate the light from the darkness.
        And God saw that it was good.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And evening passed and morning came, marking the fourth day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet the waters swarm with fish and other life.
        Let the skies be filled with birds of every kind.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So God created great sea creatures and every living thing that scurries
        and swarms in the water, and every sort of bird\u2014each producing offspring
        of the same kind. And God saw that it was good. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God blessed them, saying, \u201CBe fruitful and multiply. Let
        the fish fill the seas, and let the birds multiply on the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And evening passed and morning came, marking the fifth day.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet the earth produce every sort of animal,
        each producing offspring of the same kind\u2014livestock, small animals that
        scurry along the ground, and wild animals.\u201D And that is what happened. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'God made all sorts of wild animals, livestock, and small animals,
        each able to produce offspring of the same kind. And God saw that it was
        good.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLet us make human beings[[COMMENT(0)]] in our
        image, to be like us. They will reign over the fish in the sea, the birds
        in the sky, the livestock, all the wild animals on the earth,[[COMMENT(1)]]
        and the small animals that scurry along the ground.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '1:26a '
        content: Or <b>man; </b>Hebrew reads <b>adam.</b>
      - number: '1:26b '
        content: As in Syriac version; Hebrew reads <b>all the earth.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So God created human beings[[COMMENT(0)]] in his own image.In the
        image of God he created them;male and female he created them.  '
      comments:
      - number: '1:27 '
        content: Or <b>the man; </b>Hebrew reads <b>ha-adam.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then God blessed them and said, \u201CBe fruitful and multiply. Fill
        the earth and govern it. Reign over the fish in the sea, the birds in the
        sky, and all the animals that scurry along the ground.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CLook! I have given you every seed-bearing plant
        throughout the earth and all the fruit trees for your food. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I have given every green plant as food for all the wild animals,
        the birds in the sky, and the small animals that scurry along the ground\u2014everything
        that has life.\u201D And that is what happened.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: '  So the creation of the heavens and the earth and everything in
        them was completed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the seventh day God had finished his work of creation, so he rested[[COMMENT(0)]]
        from all his work. '
      comments:
      - number: '2:2 '
        content: Or <b>ceased; </b>also in 2:3.
    - title: 
      content: 'And God blessed the seventh day and declared it holy, because it
        was the day when he rested from all his work of creation.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Man and Woman in Eden
      content: 'This is the account of the creation of the heavens and the earth.When
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God made the earth and the heavens, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'neither wild plants nor grains were growing on the earth. For the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God had not yet sent rain to water the earth,
        and there were no people to cultivate the soil. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Instead, springs[[COMMENT(0)]] came up from the ground and watered
        all the land. '
      comments:
      - number: '2:6 '
        content: Or <b>mist.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God formed the man from the
        dust of the ground. He breathed the breath of life into the man\u2019s nostrils,
        and the man became a living person.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God planted a garden in Eden
        in the east, and there he placed the man he had made. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God made all sorts of trees grow
        up from the ground\u2014trees that were beautiful and that produced delicious
        fruit. In the middle of the garden he placed the tree of life and the tree
        of the knowledge of good and evil.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A river flowed from the land of Eden, watering the garden and then
        dividing into four branches. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The first branch, called the Pishon, flowed around the entire land
        of Havilah, where gold is found. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The gold of that land is exceptionally pure; aromatic resin and onyx
        stone are also found there. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The second branch, called the Gihon, flowed around the entire land
        of Cush. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The third branch, called the Tigris, flowed east of the land of Asshur.
        The fourth branch is called the Euphrates.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God placed the man in the Garden
        of Eden to tend and watch over it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God warned him, \u201CYou may
        freely eat the fruit of every tree in the garden\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "except the tree of the knowledge of good and evil. If you eat its
        fruit, you are sure to die.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God said, \u201CIt is not good
        for the man to be alone. I will make a helper who is just right for him.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God formed from the ground all
        the wild animals and all the birds of the sky. He brought them to the man[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to see what he would call them, and the man chose a name for each one. '
      comments:
      - number: '2:19 '
        content: Or <b>Adam, </b>and so throughout the chapter.
    - title: 
      content: 'He gave names to all the livestock, all the birds of the sky, and
        all the wild animals. But still there was no helper just right for him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God caused the man to fall into
        a deep sleep. While the man slept, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God took
        out one of the man\u2019s ribs[[COMMENT(0)]] and closed up the opening. "
      comments:
      - number: '2:21 '
        content: "Or <b>took a part of the man\u2019s side.</b>"
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God made a woman from the rib,
        and he brought her to the man.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAt last!\u201D the man exclaimed.\u201CThis one is bone from
        my bone,and flesh from my flesh!She will be called \u2018woman,\u2019because
        she was taken from \u2018man.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This explains why a man leaves his father and mother and is joined
        to his wife, and the two are united into one.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Man and Woman Sin
      content: "  The serpent was the shrewdest of all the wild animals the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        God had made. One day he asked the woman, \u201CDid God really say you must
        not eat the fruit from any of the trees in the garden?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COf course we may eat fruit from the trees in the garden,\u201D
        the woman replied. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIt\u2019s only the fruit from the tree in the middle of the
        garden that we are not allowed to eat. God said, \u2018You must not eat it
        or even touch it; if you do, you will die.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou won\u2019t die!\u201D the serpent replied to the woman. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGod knows that your eyes will be opened as soon as you eat
        it, and you will be like God, knowing both good and evil.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The woman was convinced. She saw that the tree was beautiful and
        its fruit looked delicious, and she wanted the wisdom it would give her.
        So she took some of the fruit and ate it. Then she gave some to her husband,
        who was with her, and he ate it, too. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At that moment their eyes were opened, and they suddenly felt shame
        at their nakedness. So they sewed fig leaves together to cover themselves.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the cool evening breezes were blowing, the man[[COMMENT(0)]]
        and his wife heard the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God walking about in the
        garden. So they hid from the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God among the trees. '
      comments:
      - number: '3:8 '
        content: Or <b>Adam, </b>and so throughout the chapter.
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God called to the man, \u201CWhere
        are you?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He replied, \u201CI heard you walking in the garden, so I hid. I
        was afraid because I was naked.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWho told you that you were naked?\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        God asked. \u201CHave you eaten from the tree whose fruit I commanded you
        not to eat?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The man replied, \u201CIt was the woman you gave me who gave me the
        fruit, and I ate it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God asked the woman, \u201CWhat
        have you done?\u201D\u201CThe serpent deceived me,\u201D she replied. \u201CThat\u2019s
        why I ate it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God said to the serpent,\u201CBecause
        you have done this, you are cursedmore than all animals, domestic and wild.You
        will crawl on your belly,groveling in the dust as long as you live.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I will cause hostility between you and the woman,and between
        your offspring and her offspring.He will strike[[COMMENT(0)]] your head,and
        you will strike his heel.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:15 '
        content: Or <b>bruise; </b>also in 3:15b.
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said to the woman,\u201CI will sharpen the pain of your pregnancy,and
        in pain you will give birth.And you will desire to control your husband,but
        he will rule over you.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:16 '
        content: Or <b>And though you will have desire for your husband, / he will
          rule over you.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "And to the man he said,\u201CSince you listened to your wife and
        ate from the treewhose fruit I commanded you not to eat,the ground is cursed
        because of you.All your life you will struggle to scratch a living from it.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It will grow thorns and thistles for you,though you will eat of its
        grains.  '
      comments: []
    - title: "Paradise Lost: God\u2019s Judgment"
      content: "By the sweat of your browwill you have food to eatuntil you return
        to the groundfrom which you were made.For you were made from dust,and to
        dust you will return.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the man\u2014Adam\u2014named his wife Eve, because she would
        be the mother of all who live.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '3:20 '
        content: "<b>Eve </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Cto give life.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God made clothing from animal
        skins for Adam and his wife.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God said, \u201CLook, the human
        beings[[COMMENT(0)]] have become like us, knowing both good and evil. What
        if they reach out, take fruit from the tree of life, and eat it? Then they
        will live forever!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '3:22 '
        content: Or <b>the man; </b>Hebrew reads <b>ha-adam.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> God banished them from the Garden
        of Eden, and he sent Adam out to cultivate the ground from which he had been
        made. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Cain and Abel
      content: "  Now Adam[[COMMENT(0)]] had sexual relations with his wife, Eve,
        and she became pregnant. When she gave birth to Cain, she said, \u201CWith
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s help, I have produced[[COMMENT(1)]]
        a man!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '4:1a '
        content: Or <b>the man; </b>also in 4:25.
      - number: '4:1b '
        content: "Or <b>I have acquired. </b><b>Cain </b>sounds like a Hebrew term
          that can mean \u201Cproduce\u201D or \u201Cacquire.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Later she gave birth to his brother and named him Abel.When they
        grew up, Abel became a shepherd, while Cain cultivated the ground. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When it was time for the harvest, Cain presented some of his crops
        as a gift to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abel also brought a gift\u2014the best portions of the firstborn
        lambs from his flock. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> accepted Abel and his
        gift, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'but he did not accept Cain and his gift. This made Cain very angry,
        and he looked dejected.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy are you so angry?\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        asked Cain. \u201CWhy do you look so dejected? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will be accepted if you do what is right. But if you refuse to
        do what is right, then watch out! Sin is crouching at the door, eager to
        control you. But you must subdue it and be its master.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Cain suggested to his brother, \u201CLet\u2019s go out into
        the fields.\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]] And while they were in the field, Cain attacked
        his brother, Abel, and killed him.  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:8 '
        content: "As in Samaritan Pentateuch, Greek and Syriac versions, and Latin
          Vulgate; Masoretic Text lacks <b>\u201CLet\u2019s go out into the fields.\u201D</b>"
    - title: 
      content: "Afterward the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> asked Cain, \u201CWhere
        is your brother? Where is Abel?\u201D\u201CI don\u2019t know,\u201D Cain
        responded. \u201CAm I my brother\u2019s guardian?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CWhat have you done?
        Listen! Your brother\u2019s blood cries out to me from the ground! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now you are cursed and banished from the ground, which has swallowed
        your brother\u2019s blood. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No longer will the ground yield good crops for you, no matter how
        hard you work! From now on you will be a homeless wanderer on the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Cain replied to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, \u201CMy punishment[[COMMENT(0)]]
        is too great for me to bear! "
      comments:
      - number: '4:13 '
        content: Or <b>My sin.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "You have banished me from the land and from your presence; you have
        made me a homeless wanderer. Anyone who finds me will kill me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CNo, for I will give
        a sevenfold punishment to anyone who kills you.\u201D Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        put a mark on Cain to warn anyone who might try to kill him. "
      comments: []
    - title: The Descendants of Cain
      content: "So Cain left the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence and
        settled in the land of Nod,[[COMMENT(0)]] east of Eden.  "
      comments:
      - number: '4:16 '
        content: "<b>Nod </b>means \u201Cwandering.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Cain had sexual relations with his wife, and she became pregnant
        and gave birth to Enoch. Then Cain founded a city, which he named Enoch,
        after his son. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Enoch had a son named Irad. Irad became the father of[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Mehujael. Mehujael became the father of Methushael. Methushael became the
        father of Lamech.  '
      comments:
      - number: '4:18 '
        content: Or <b>the ancestor of, </b>and so throughout the verse.
    - title: 
      content: 'Lamech married two women. The first was named Adah, and the second
        was Zillah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Adah gave birth to Jabal, who was the first of those who raise livestock
        and live in tents. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "His brother\u2019s name was Jubal, the first of all who play the
        harp and flute. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Lamech\u2019s other wife, Zillah, gave birth to a son named Tubal-cain.
        He became an expert in forging tools of bronze and iron. Tubal-cain had a
        sister named Naamah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Lamech said to his wives,\u201CAdah and Zillah, hear my voice;listen
        to me, you wives of Lamech.I have killed a man who attacked me,a young man
        who wounded me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: The Birth of Seth
      content: "If someone who kills Cain is punished seven times,then the one who
        kills me will be punished seventy-seven times!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Adam had sexual relations with his wife again, and she gave birth
        to another son. She named him Seth,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CGod
        has granted me another son in place of Abel, whom Cain killed.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '4:25 '
        content: "<b>Seth </b>probably means \u201Cgranted\u201D; the name may also
          mean \u201Cappointed.\u201D"
  - verses:
    - title: The Descendants of Adam
      content: '  This is the written account of the descendants of Adam. When God
        created human beings,[[COMMENT(0)]] he made them to be like himself. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:1 '
        content: Or <b>man; </b>Hebrew reads <b>adam; </b>similarly in 5:2.
    - title: 
      content: "He created them male and female, and he blessed them and called them
        \u201Chuman.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Adam was 130 years old, he became the father of a son who was
        just like him\u2014in his very image. He named his son Seth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Seth, Adam lived another 800 years, and he had
        other sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Adam lived 930 years, and then he died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Seth was 105 years old, he became the father of[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Enosh. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:6 '
        content: Or <b>the ancestor of; </b>also in 5:9, 12, 15, 18, 21, 25.
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of[[COMMENT(0)]] Enosh, Seth lived another 807 years,
        and he had other sons and daughters. '
      comments:
      - number: '5:7 '
        content: Or <b>the birth of this ancestor of; </b>also in 5:10, 13, 16, 19,
          22, 26.
    - title: 
      content: 'Seth lived 912 years, and then he died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Enosh was 90 years old, he became the father of Kenan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Kenan, Enosh lived another 815 years, and he had
        other sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Enosh lived 905 years, and then he died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Kenan was 70 years old, he became the father of Mahalalel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Mahalalel, Kenan lived another 840 years, and
        he had other sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Kenan lived 910 years, and then he died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Mahalalel was 65 years old, he became the father of Jared. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Jared, Mahalalel lived another 830 years, and
        he had other sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Mahalalel lived 895 years, and then he died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Jared was 162 years old, he became the father of Enoch. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Enoch, Jared lived another 800 years, and he had
        other sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jared lived 962 years, and then he died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Enoch was 65 years old, he became the father of Methuselah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Methuselah, Enoch lived in close fellowship with
        God for another 300 years, and he had other sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Enoch lived 365 years, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'walking in close fellowship with God. Then one day he disappeared,
        because God took him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Methuselah was 187 years old, he became the father of Lamech. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Lamech, Methuselah lived another 782 years, and
        he had other sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Methuselah lived 969 years, and then he died.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Lamech was 182 years old, he became the father of a son. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Lamech named his son Noah, for he said, \u201CMay he bring us relief[[COMMENT(0)]]
        from our work and the painful labor of farming this ground that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has cursed.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '5:29 '
        content: "<b>Noah </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that can mean \u201Crelief\u201D
          or \u201Ccomfort.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Noah, Lamech lived another 595 years, and he had
        other sons and daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Lamech lived 777 years, and then he died.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A World Gone Wrong
      content: '  Then the people began to multiply on the earth, and daughters were
        born to them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of God saw the beautiful women[[COMMENT(0)]] and took any
        they wanted as their wives. '
      comments:
      - number: '6:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>daughters of men; </b>also in 6:4.
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CMy Spirit will not
        put up with[[COMMENT(0)]] humans for such a long time, for they are only
        mortal flesh. In the future, their normal lifespan will be no more than 120
        years.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:3 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>will not remain in.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'In those days, and for some time after, giant Nephilites lived on
        the earth, for whenever the sons of God had intercourse with women, they
        gave birth to children who became the heroes and famous warriors of ancient
        times.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> observed the extent of human wickedness
        on the earth, and he saw that everything they thought or imagined was consistently
        and totally evil. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was sorry he had ever made them
        and put them on the earth. It broke his heart. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CI will wipe this
        human race I have created from the face of the earth. Yes, and I will destroy
        every living thing\u2014all the people, the large animals, the small animals
        that scurry along the ground, and even the birds of the sky. I am sorry I
        ever made them.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: The Story of Noah
      content: 'But Noah found favor with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is the account of Noah and his family. Noah was a righteous
        man, the only blameless person living on earth at the time, and he walked
        in close fellowship with God. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Noah was the father of three sons: Shem, Ham, and Japheth.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now God saw that the earth had become corrupt and was filled with
        violence. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'God observed all this corruption in the world, for everyone on earth
        was corrupt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So God said to Noah, \u201CI have decided to destroy all living creatures,
        for they have filled the earth with violence. Yes, I will wipe them all out
        along with the earth!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBuild a large boat[[COMMENT(0)]] from cypress wood[[COMMENT(1)]]
        and waterproof it with tar, inside and out. Then construct decks and stalls
        throughout its interior. "
      comments:
      - number: '6:14a '
        content: Traditionally rendered <b>an ark.</b>
      - number: '6:14b '
        content: Or <b>gopher wood.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Make the boat 450 feet long, 75 feet wide, and 45 feet high.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '6:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>300 cubits </b>[138 meters] <b>long, 50 cubits </b>[23
          meters] <b>wide, and 30 cubits </b>[13.8 meters] <b>high.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Leave an 18-inch opening[[COMMENT(0)]] below the roof all the way
        around the boat. Put the door on the side, and build three decks inside the
        boat\u2014lower, middle, and upper.  "
      comments:
      - number: '6:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>an opening of 1 cubit </b>[46 centimeters].
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLook! I am about to cover the earth with a flood that will
        destroy every living thing that breathes. Everything on earth will die. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I will confirm my covenant with you. So enter the boat\u2014you
        and your wife and your sons and their wives. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Bring a pair of every kind of animal\u2014a male and a female\u2014into
        the boat with you to keep them alive during the flood. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pairs of every kind of bird, and every kind of animal, and every
        kind of small animal that scurries along the ground, will come to you to
        be kept alive. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And be sure to take on board enough food for your family and for
        all the animals.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Flood Covers the Earth
      content: "  When everything was ready, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said
        to Noah, \u201CGo into the boat with all your family, for among all the people
        of the earth, I can see that you alone are righteous. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Take with you seven pairs\u2014male and female\u2014of each animal
        I have approved for eating and for sacrifice,[[COMMENT(0)]] and take one
        pair of each of the others. "
      comments:
      - number: '7:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>of each clean animal; </b>similarly in 7:8.
    - title: 
      content: 'Also take seven pairs of every kind of bird. There must be a male
        and a female in each pair to ensure that all life will survive on the earth
        after the flood. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Seven days from now I will make the rains pour down on the earth.
        And it will rain for forty days and forty nights, until I have wiped from
        the earth all the living things I have created.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Noah did everything as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> commanded
        him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Noah was 600 years old when the flood covered the earth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He went on board the boat to escape the flood\u2014he and his wife
        and his sons and their wives. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "With them were all the various kinds of animals\u2014those approved
        for eating and for sacrifice and those that were not\u2014along with all
        the birds and the small animals that scurry along the ground. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They entered the boat in pairs, male and female, just as God had
        commanded Noah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After seven days, the waters of the flood came and covered the earth.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Noah was 600 years old, on the seventeenth day of the second
        month, all the underground waters erupted from the earth, and the rain fell
        in mighty torrents from the sky. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The rain continued to fall for forty days and forty nights.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "That very day Noah had gone into the boat with his wife and his sons\u2014Shem,
        Ham, and Japheth\u2014and their wives. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "With them in the boat were pairs of every kind of animal\u2014domestic
        and wild, large and small\u2014along with birds of every kind. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Two by two they came into the boat, representing every living thing
        that breathes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A male and female of each kind entered, just as God had commanded
        Noah. Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> closed the door behind them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'For forty days the floodwaters grew deeper, covering the ground and
        lifting the boat high above the earth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As the waters rose higher and higher above the ground, the boat floated
        safely on the surface. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Finally, the water covered even the highest mountains on the earth, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'rising more than twenty-two feet[[COMMENT(0)]] above the highest
        peaks. '
      comments:
      - number: '7:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>15 cubits </b>[6.9 meters].
    - title: 
      content: "All the living things on earth died\u2014birds, domestic animals,
        wild animals, small animals that scurry along the ground, and all the people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Everything that breathed and lived on dry land died. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "God wiped out every living thing on the earth\u2014people, livestock,
        small animals that scurry along the ground, and the birds of the sky. All
        were destroyed. The only people who survived were Noah and those with him
        in the boat. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Flood Recedes
      content: '  But God remembered Noah and all the wild animals and livestock
        with him in the boat. He sent a wind to blow across the earth, and the floodwaters
        began to recede. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The underground waters stopped flowing, and the torrential rains
        from the sky were stopped. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the floodwaters gradually receded from the earth. After 150 days, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'exactly five months from the time the flood began,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        the boat came to rest on the mountains of Ararat. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>on the seventeenth day of the seventh month; </b>see 7:11.
    - title: 
      content: 'Two and a half months later,[[COMMENT(0)]] as the waters continued
        to go down, other mountain peaks became visible.  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:5 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the first day of the tenth month; </b>see 7:11 and
          note on 8:4.
    - title: 
      content: 'After another forty days, Noah opened the window he had made in the
        boat '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and released a raven. The bird flew back and forth until the floodwaters
        on the earth had dried up. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also released a dove to see if the water had receded and it could
        find dry ground. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the dove could find no place to land because the water still
        covered the ground. So it returned to the boat, and Noah held out his hand
        and drew the dove back inside. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After waiting another seven days, Noah released the dove again. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This time the dove returned to him in the evening with a fresh olive
        leaf in its beak. Then Noah knew that the floodwaters were almost gone. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He waited another seven days and then released the dove again. This
        time it did not come back.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Noah was now 601 years old. On the first day of the new year, ten
        and a half months after the flood began,[[COMMENT(0)]] the floodwaters had
        almost dried up from the earth. Noah lifted back the covering of the boat
        and saw that the surface of the ground was drying. '
      comments:
      - number: '8:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>On the first day of the first month; </b>see 7:11.
    - title: 
      content: 'Two more months went by,[[COMMENT(0)]] and at last the earth was
        dry!  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>The twenty-seventh day of the second month arrived; </b>see
          note on 8:13.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then God said to Noah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLeave the boat, all of you\u2014you and your wife, and your
        sons and their wives. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Release all the animals\u2014the birds, the livestock, and the small
        animals that scurry along the ground\u2014so they can be fruitful and multiply
        throughout the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Noah, his wife, and his sons and their wives left the boat. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And all of the large and small animals and birds came out of the
        boat, pair by pair.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Noah built an altar to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and
        there he sacrificed as burnt offerings the animals and birds that had been
        approved for that purpose.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '8:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>every clean animal and every clean bird.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was pleased with the aroma of
        the sacrifice and said to himself, \u201CI will never again curse the ground
        because of the human race, even though everything they think or imagine is
        bent toward evil from childhood. I will never again destroy all living things. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: God Confirms His Covenant
      content: "  Then God blessed Noah and his sons and told them, \u201CBe fruitful
        and multiply. Fill the earth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All the animals of the earth, all the birds of the sky, all the small
        animals that scurry along the ground, and all the fish in the sea will look
        on you with fear and terror. I have placed them in your power. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I have given them to you for food, just as I have given you grain
        and vegetables. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But you must never eat any meat that still has the lifeblood in it.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd I will require the blood of anyone who takes another person\u2019s
        life. If a wild animal kills a person, it must die. And anyone who murders
        a fellow human must die. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If anyone takes a human life, that person\u2019s life will also be
        taken by human hands. For God made human beings[[COMMENT(0)]] in his own
        image. "
      comments:
      - number: '9:6 '
        content: Or <b>man; </b>Hebrew reads <b>ha-adam.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Now be fruitful and multiply, and repopulate the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then God told Noah and his sons, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI hereby confirm my covenant with you and your descendants, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and with all the animals that were on the boat with you\u2014the
        birds, the livestock, and all the wild animals\u2014every living creature
        on earth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yes, I am confirming my covenant with you. Never again will floodwaters
        kill all living creatures; never again will a flood destroy the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CI am giving you a sign of my covenant with you
        and with all living creatures, for all generations to come. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I have placed my rainbow in the clouds. It is the sign of my covenant
        with you and with all the earth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When I send clouds over the earth, the rainbow will appear in the
        clouds, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and I will remember my covenant with you and with all living creatures.
        Never again will the floodwaters destroy all life. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When I see the rainbow in the clouds, I will remember the eternal
        covenant between God and every living creature on earth.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: "Noah\u2019s Sons"
      content: "Then God said to Noah, \u201CYes, this rainbow is the sign of the
        covenant I am confirming with all the creatures on earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Noah who came out of the boat with their father were
        Shem, Ham, and Japheth. (Ham is the father of Canaan.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From these three sons of Noah came all the people who now populate
        the earth.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the flood, Noah began to cultivate the ground, and he planted
        a vineyard. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One day he drank some wine he had made, and he became drunk and lay
        naked inside his tent. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ham, the father of Canaan, saw that his father was naked and went
        outside and told his brothers. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Shem and Japheth took a robe, held it over their shoulders,
        and backed into the tent to cover their father. As they did this, they looked
        the other way so they would not see him naked.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Noah woke up from his stupor, he learned what Ham, his youngest
        son, had done. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he cursed Canaan, the son of Ham:\u201CMay Canaan be cursed!May
        he be the lowest of servants to his relatives.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Noah said,\u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God
        of Shem, be blessed,and may Canaan be his servant!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "May God expand the territory of Japheth!May Japheth share the prosperity
        of Shem,[[COMMENT(0)]]and may Canaan be his servant.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '9:27 '
        content: Hebrew <b>May he live in the tents of Shem.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Noah lived another 350 years after the great flood. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Descendants of Japheth
      content: '  This is the account of the families of Shem, Ham, and Japheth,
        the three sons of Noah. Many children were born to them after the great flood.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Japheth were Gomer, Magog, Madai, Javan, Tubal,
        Meshech, and Tiras.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Gomer were Ashkenaz, Riphath, and Togarmah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Javan were Elishah, Tarshish, Kittim, and Rodanim.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:4 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts and Greek version (see also 1 Chr
          1:7); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>Dodanim.</b>
    - title: Descendants of Ham
      content: 'Their descendants became the seafaring peoples that spread out to
        various lands, each identified by its own language, clan, and national identity.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Ham were Cush, Mizraim, Put, and Canaan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Cush were Seba, Havilah, Sabtah, Raamah, and Sabteca.
        The descendants of Raamah were Sheba and Dedan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Cush was also the ancestor of Nimrod, who was the first heroic warrior
        on earth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Since he was the greatest hunter in the world,[[COMMENT(0)]]<smallcaps>also
        in 10:9b.</smallcaps> his name became proverbial. People would say, \u201CThis
        man is like Nimrod, the greatest hunter in the world.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '10:9 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a great hunter before the <span class="ChapterContent_nd__ECPAf">Lord</span>;
          </b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He built his kingdom in the land of Babylonia,[[COMMENT(0)]] with
        the cities of Babylon, Erech, Akkad, and Calneh. '
      comments:
      - number: '10:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shinar.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'From there he expanded his territory to Assyria,[[COMMENT(0)]] building
        the cities of Nineveh, Rehoboth-ir, Calah, '
      comments:
      - number: '10:11 '
        content: Or <b>From that land Assyria went out.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'and Resen (the great city located between Nineveh and Calah).  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Mizraim was the ancestor of the Ludites, Anamites, Lehabites, Naphtuhites, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pathrusites, Casluhites, and the Caphtorites, from whom the Philistines
        came.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Casluhites, from whom the Philistines came, and Caphtorites.
          </b>Compare Jer 47:4; Amos 9:7.
    - title: 
      content: "Canaan\u2019s oldest son was Sidon, the ancestor of the Sidonians.
        Canaan was also the ancestor of the Hittites,[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '10:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>ancestor of Heth.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Jebusites, Amorites, Girgashites, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hivites, Arkites, Sinites, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Arvadites, Zemarites, and Hamathites. The Canaanite clans eventually
        spread out, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and the territory of Canaan extended from Sidon in the north to Gerar
        and Gaza in the south, and east as far as Sodom, Gomorrah, Admah, and Zeboiim,
        near Lasha.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Descendants of Shem
      content: 'These were the descendants of Ham, identified by clan, language,
        territory, and national identity.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Sons were also born to Shem, the older brother of Japheth.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Shem was the ancestor of all the descendants of Eber.  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:21 '
        content: Or <b>Shem, whose older brother was Japheth.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Shem were Elam, Asshur, Arphaxad, Lud, and Aram.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Aram were Uz, Hul, Gether, and Mash.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Arphaxad was the father of Shelah,[[COMMENT(0)]] and Shelah was the
        father of Eber.  '
      comments:
      - number: '10:24 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>Arphaxad was the father of Cainan, Cainan
          was the father of Shelah. </b>Compare Luke 3:36.
    - title: 
      content: "Eber had two sons. The first was named Peleg (which means \u201Cdivision\u201D),
        for during his lifetime the people of the world were divided into different
        language groups. His brother\u2019s name was Joktan.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joktan was the ancestor of Almodad, Sheleph, Hazarmaveth, Jerah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hadoram, Uzal, Diklah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Obal, Abimael, Sheba, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ophir, Havilah, and Jobab. All these were descendants of Joktan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The territory they occupied extended from Mesha all the way to Sephar
        in the eastern mountains.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Conclusion
      content: 'These were the descendants of Shem, identified by clan, language,
        territory, and national identity.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Tower of Babel
      content: '  At one time all the people of the world spoke the same language
        and used the same words. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As the people migrated to the east, they found a plain in the land
        of Babylonia[[COMMENT(0)]] and settled there.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shinar.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "They began saying to each other, \u201CLet\u2019s make bricks and
        harden them with fire.\u201D (In this region bricks were used instead of
        stone, and tar was used for mortar.) "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then they said, \u201CCome, let\u2019s build a great city for ourselves
        with a tower that reaches into the sky. This will make us famous and keep
        us from being scattered all over the world.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> came down to look at the city
        and the tower the people were building. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLook!\u201D he said. \u201CThe people are united, and they
        all speak the same language. After this, nothing they set out to do will
        be impossible for them! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Come, let\u2019s go down and confuse the people with different languages.
        Then they won\u2019t be able to understand each other.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In that way, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> scattered them all over
        the world, and they stopped building the city. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Line of Descent from Shem to Abram
      content: 'That is why the city was called Babel,[[COMMENT(0)]] because that
        is where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> confused the people with different
        languages. In this way he scattered them all over the world.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:9 '
        content: "Or <b>Babylon. </b><b>Babel </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that
          means \u201Cconfusion.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "This is the account of Shem\u2019s family.Two years after the great
        flood, when Shem was 100 years old, he became the father of[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Arphaxad. "
      comments:
      - number: '11:10 '
        content: Or <b>the ancestor of; </b>also in 11:12, 14, 16, 18, 20, 22, 24.
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of[[COMMENT(0)]] Arphaxad, Shem lived another 500
        years and had other sons and daughters.  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:11 '
        content: Or <b>the birth of this ancestor of; </b>also in 11:13, 15, 17,
          19, 21, 23, 25.
    - title: 
      content: 'When Arphaxad was 35 years old, he became the father of Shelah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Shelah, Arphaxad lived another 403 years and had
        other sons and daughters.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '11:12-13 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>When Arphaxad was 135 years old, he became
          the father of Cainan. </b><b>After the birth of Cainan, Arphaxad lived
          another 430 years and had other sons and daughters, and then he died. When
          Cainan was 130 years old, he became the father of Shelah. After the birth
          of Shelah, Cainan lived another 330 years and had other sons and daughters,
          and then he died. </b>Compare Luke 3:35-36.
    - title: 
      content: 'When Shelah was 30 years old, he became the father of Eber. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Eber, Shelah lived another 403 years and had other
        sons and daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Eber was 34 years old, he became the father of Peleg. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Peleg, Eber lived another 430 years and had other
        sons and daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Peleg was 30 years old, he became the father of Reu. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Reu, Peleg lived another 209 years and had other
        sons and daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Reu was 32 years old, he became the father of Serug. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Serug, Reu lived another 207 years and had other
        sons and daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Serug was 30 years old, he became the father of Nahor. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Nahor, Serug lived another 200 years and had other
        sons and daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Nahor was 29 years old, he became the father of Terah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the birth of Terah, Nahor lived another 119 years and had other
        sons and daughters.  '
      comments: []
    - title: The Family of Terah
      content: 'After Terah was 70 years old, he became the father of Abram, Nahor,
        and Haran.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is the account of Terah\u2019s family. Terah was the father
        of Abram, Nahor, and Haran; and Haran was the father of Lot. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Haran died in Ur of the Chaldeans, the land of his birth, while
        his father, Terah, was still living. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, Abram and Nahor both married. The name of Abram\u2019s
        wife was Sarai, and the name of Nahor\u2019s wife was Milcah. (Milcah and
        her sister Iscah were daughters of Nahor\u2019s brother Haran.) "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Sarai was unable to become pregnant and had no children.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Terah took his son Abram, his daughter-in-law Sarai (his
        son Abram\u2019s wife), and his grandson Lot (his son Haran\u2019s child)
        and moved away from Ur of the Chaldeans. He was headed for the land of Canaan,
        but they stopped at Haran and settled there. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Call of Abram
      content: "  The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had said to Abram, \u201CLeave
        your native country, your relatives, and your father\u2019s family, and go
        to the land that I will show you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will make you into a great nation. I will bless you and make you
        famous, and you will be a blessing to others. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will bless those who bless you and curse those who treat you with
        contempt. All the families on earth will be blessed through you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Abram departed as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had instructed,
        and Lot went with him. Abram was seventy-five years old when he left Haran. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He took his wife, Sarai, his nephew Lot, and all his wealth\u2014his
        livestock and all the people he had taken into his household at Haran\u2014and
        headed for the land of Canaan. When they arrived in Canaan, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abram traveled through the land as far as Shechem. There he set up
        camp beside the oak of Moreh. At that time, the area was inhabited by Canaanites.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared to Abram and said,
        \u201CI will give this land to your descendants.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u201D And
        Abram built an altar there and dedicated it to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who had appeared to him. "
      comments:
      - number: '12:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>seed.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'After that, Abram traveled south and set up camp in the hill country,
        with Bethel to the west and Ai to the east. There he built another altar
        and dedicated it to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and he worshiped the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: Abram and Sarai in Egypt
      content: 'Then Abram continued traveling south by stages toward the Negev.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At that time a severe famine struck the land of Canaan, forcing Abram
        to go down to Egypt, where he lived as a foreigner. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As he was approaching the border of Egypt, Abram said to his wife,
        Sarai, \u201CLook, you are a very beautiful woman. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the Egyptians see you, they will say, \u2018This is his wife.
        Let\u2019s kill him; then we can have her!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So please tell them you are my sister. Then they will spare my life
        and treat me well because of their interest in you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And sure enough, when Abram arrived in Egypt, everyone noticed Sarai\u2019s
        beauty. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the palace officials saw her, they sang her praises to Pharaoh,
        their king, and Sarai was taken into his palace. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh gave Abram many gifts because of her\u2014sheep, goats,
        cattle, male and female donkeys, male and female servants, and camels.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> sent terrible plagues upon Pharaoh
        and his household because of Sarai, Abram\u2019s wife. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Pharaoh summoned Abram and accused him sharply. \u201CWhat have
        you done to me?\u201D he demanded. \u201CWhy didn\u2019t you tell me she
        was your wife? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why did you say, \u2018She is my sister,\u2019 and allow me to take
        her as my wife? Now then, here is your wife. Take her and get out of here!\u201D "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Abram and Lot Separate
      content: '  So Abram left Egypt and traveled north into the Negev, along with
        his wife and Lot and all that they owned. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(Abram was very rich in livestock, silver, and gold.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From the Negev, they continued traveling by stages toward Bethel,
        and they pitched their tents between Bethel and Ai, where they had camped
        before. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This was the same place where Abram had built the altar, and there
        he worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> again.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Lot, who was traveling with Abram, had also become very wealthy with
        flocks of sheep and goats, herds of cattle, and many tents. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the land could not support both Abram and Lot with all their
        flocks and herds living so close together. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So disputes broke out between the herdsmen of Abram and Lot. (At
        that time Canaanites and Perizzites were also living in the land.)  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally Abram said to Lot, \u201CLet\u2019s not allow this conflict
        to come between us or our herdsmen. After all, we are close relatives! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The whole countryside is open to you. Take your choice of any section
        of the land you want, and we will separate. If you want the land to the left,
        then I\u2019ll take the land on the right. If you prefer the land on the
        right, then I\u2019ll go to the left.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Lot took a long look at the fertile plains of the Jordan Valley in
        the direction of Zoar. The whole area was well watered everywhere, like the
        garden of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> or the beautiful land of Egypt.
        (This was before the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> destroyed Sodom and Gomorrah.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Lot chose for himself the whole Jordan Valley to the east of them.
        He went there with his flocks and servants and parted company with his uncle
        Abram. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Abram settled in the land of Canaan, and Lot moved his tents to
        a place near Sodom and settled among the cities of the plain. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the people of this area were extremely wicked and constantly
        sinned against the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After Lot had gone, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Abram,
        \u201CLook as far as you can see in every direction\u2014north and south,
        east and west. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I am giving all this land, as far as you can see, to you and your
        descendants[[COMMENT(0)]] as a permanent possession. '
      comments:
      - number: '13:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>seed; </b>also in 13:16.
    - title: 
      content: 'And I will give you so many descendants that, like the dust of the
        earth, they cannot be counted! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Go and walk through the land in every direction, for I am giving
        it to you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Abram Rescues Lot
      content: '  About this time war broke out in the region. King Amraphel of Babylonia,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        King Arioch of Ellasar, King Kedorlaomer of Elam, and King Tidal of Goiim '
      comments:
      - number: '14:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Shinar; </b>also in 14:9.
    - title: 
      content: 'fought against King Bera of Sodom, King Birsha of Gomorrah, King
        Shinab of Admah, King Shemeber of Zeboiim, and the king of Bela (also called
        Zoar).  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This second group of kings joined forces in Siddim Valley (that is,
        the valley of the Dead Sea[[COMMENT(0)]]). '
      comments:
      - number: '14:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Salt Sea.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'For twelve years they had been subject to King Kedorlaomer, but in
        the thirteenth year they rebelled against him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One year later Kedorlaomer and his allies arrived and defeated the
        Rephaites at Ashteroth-karnaim, the Zuzites at Ham, the Emites at Shaveh-kiriathaim, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and the Horites at Mount Seir, as far as El-paran at the edge of
        the wilderness. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they turned back and came to En-mishpat (now called Kadesh)
        and conquered all the territory of the Amalekites, and also the Amorites
        living in Hazazon-tamar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the rebel kings of Sodom, Gomorrah, Admah, Zeboiim, and Bela
        (also called Zoar) prepared for battle in the valley of the Dead Sea.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '14:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Siddim Valley </b>(see 14:3); also in 14:10.
    - title: 
      content: "They fought against King Kedorlaomer of Elam, King Tidal of Goiim,
        King Amraphel of Babylonia, and King Arioch of Ellasar\u2014four kings against
        five. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As it happened, the valley of the Dead Sea was filled with tar pits.
        And as the army of the kings of Sodom and Gomorrah fled, some fell into the
        tar pits, while the rest escaped into the mountains. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The victorious invaders then plundered Sodom and Gomorrah and headed
        for home, taking with them all the spoils of war and the food supplies. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They also captured Lot\u2014Abram\u2019s nephew who lived in Sodom\u2014and
        carried off everything he owned.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But one of Lot\u2019s men escaped and reported everything to Abram
        the Hebrew, who was living near the oak grove belonging to Mamre the Amorite.
        Mamre and his relatives, Eshcol and Aner, were Abram\u2019s allies.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Abram heard that his nephew Lot had been captured, he mobilized
        the 318 trained men who had been born into his household. Then he pursued
        Kedorlaomer\u2019s army until he caught up with them at Dan. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "There he divided his men and attacked during the night. Kedorlaomer\u2019s
        army fled, but Abram chased them as far as Hobah, north of Damascus. "
      comments: []
    - title: Melchizedek Blesses Abram
      content: 'Abram recovered all the goods that had been taken, and he brought
        back his nephew Lot with his possessions and all the women and other captives.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After Abram returned from his victory over Kedorlaomer and all his
        allies, the king of Sodom went out to meet him in the valley of Shaveh (that
        is, the King\u2019s Valley).  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And Melchizedek, the king of Salem and a priest of God Most High,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        brought Abram some bread and wine. '
      comments:
      - number: '14:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>El-Elyon; </b>also in 14:19, 20, 22.
    - title: 
      content: "Melchizedek blessed Abram with this blessing:\u201CBlessed be Abram
        by God Most High,Creator of heaven and earth.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And blessed be God Most High,who has defeated your enemies for you.\u201DThen
        Abram gave Melchizedek a tenth of all the goods he had recovered.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The king of Sodom said to Abram, \u201CGive back my people who were
        captured. But you may keep for yourself all the goods you have recovered.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abram replied to the king of Sodom, \u201CI solemnly swear to the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God Most High, Creator of heaven and earth, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "that I will not take so much as a single thread or sandal thong from
        what belongs to you. Otherwise you might say, \u2018I am the one who made
        Abram rich.\u2019 "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s Covenant Promise to Abram"
      content: "  Some time later, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> spoke to Abram
        in a vision and said to him, \u201CDo not be afraid, Abram, for I will protect
        you, and your reward will be great.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Abram replied, \u201CO Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        what good are all your blessings when I don\u2019t even have a son? Since
        you\u2019ve given me no children, Eliezer of Damascus, a servant in my household,
        will inherit all my wealth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You have given me no descendants of my own, so one of my servants
        will be my heir.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to him, \u201CNo, your
        servant will not be your heir, for you will have a son of your own who will
        be your heir.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> took Abram outside and said
        to him, \u201CLook up into the sky and count the stars if you can. That\u2019s
        how many descendants you will have!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And Abram believed the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        counted him as righteous because of his faith.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him, \u201CI am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        who brought you out of Ur of the Chaldeans to give you this land as your
        possession.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Abram replied, \u201CO Sovereign <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        how can I be sure that I will actually possess it?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told him, \u201CBring me a three-year-old
        heifer, a three-year-old female goat, a three-year-old ram, a turtledove,
        and a young pigeon.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Abram presented all these to him and killed them. Then he cut
        each animal down the middle and laid the halves side by side; he did not,
        however, cut the birds in half. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Some vultures swooped down to eat the carcasses, but Abram chased
        them away.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As the sun was going down, Abram fell into a deep sleep, and a terrifying
        darkness came down over him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Abram, \u201CYou can
        be sure that your descendants will be strangers in a foreign land, where
        they will be oppressed as slaves for 400 years. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But I will punish the nation that enslaves them, and in the end they
        will come away with great wealth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(As for you, you will die in peace and be buried at a ripe old age.) '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After four generations your descendants will return here to this
        land, for the sins of the Amorites do not yet warrant their destruction.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After the sun went down and darkness fell, Abram saw a smoking firepot
        and a flaming torch pass between the halves of the carcasses. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made a covenant with Abram that
        day and said, \u201CI have given this land to your descendants, all the way
        from the border of Egypt[[COMMENT(0)]] to the great Euphrates River\u2014 "
      comments:
      - number: '15:18 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the river of Egypt, </b>referring either to an eastern
          branch of the Nile River or to the Brook of Egypt in the Sinai (see Num
          34:5).
    - title: 
      content: 'the land now occupied by the Kenites, Kenizzites, Kadmonites, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hittites, Perizzites, Rephaites, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Birth of Ishmael
      content: "  Now Sarai, Abram\u2019s wife, had not been able to bear children
        for him. But she had an Egyptian servant named Hagar. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Sarai said to Abram, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has
        prevented me from having children. Go and sleep with my servant. Perhaps
        I can have children through her.\u201D And Abram agreed with Sarai\u2019s
        proposal. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Sarai, Abram\u2019s wife, took Hagar the Egyptian servant and
        gave her to Abram as a wife. (This happened ten years after Abram had settled
        in the land of Canaan.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Abram had sexual relations with Hagar, and she became pregnant.
        But when Hagar knew she was pregnant, she began to treat her mistress, Sarai,
        with contempt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Sarai said to Abram, \u201CThis is all your fault! I put my
        servant into your arms, but now that she\u2019s pregnant she treats me with
        contempt. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> will show who\u2019s wrong\u2014you
        or me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abram replied, \u201CLook, she is your servant, so deal with her
        as you see fit.\u201D Then Sarai treated Hagar so harshly that she finally
        ran away.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> found Hagar beside a
        spring of water in the wilderness, along the road to Shur. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The angel said to her, \u201CHagar, Sarai\u2019s servant, where have
        you come from, and where are you going?\u201D\u201CI\u2019m running away
        from my mistress, Sarai,\u201D she replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to her, \u201CReturn
        to your mistress, and submit to her authority.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he added, \u201CI will give you more descendants than you can
        count.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the angel also said, \u201CYou are now pregnant and will give
        birth to a son. You are to name him Ishmael (which means \u2018God hears\u2019),
        for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has heard your cry of distress. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This son of yours will be a wild man, as untamed as a wild donkey!
        He will raise his fist against everyone, and everyone will be against him.
        Yes, he will live in open hostility against all his relatives.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Thereafter, Hagar used another name to refer to the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        who had spoken to her. She said, \u201CYou are the God who sees me.\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]]
        She also said, \u201CHave I truly seen the One who sees me?\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '16:13 '
        content: Hebrew <b>El-roi.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So that well was named Beer-lahai-roi (which means \u201Cwell of
        the Living One who sees me\u201D). It can still be found between Kadesh and
        Bered.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Hagar gave Abram a son, and Abram named him Ishmael. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Abram Is Named Abraham
      content: "  When Abram was ninety-nine years old, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        appeared to him and said, \u201CI am El-Shaddai\u2014\u2018God Almighty.\u2019
        Serve me faithfully and live a blameless life. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will make a covenant with you, by which I will guarantee to give
        you countless descendants.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At this, Abram fell face down on the ground. Then God said to him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is my covenant with you: I will make you the father of
        a multitude of nations! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What\u2019s more, I am changing your name. It will no longer be Abram.
        Instead, you will be called Abraham,[[COMMENT(0)]] for you will be the father
        of many nations. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:5 '
        content: "<b>Abram </b>means \u201Cexalted father\u201D; <b>Abraham </b>sounds
          like a Hebrew term that means \u201Cfather of many.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'I will make you extremely fruitful. Your descendants will become
        many nations, and kings will be among them!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI will confirm my covenant with you and your descendants[[COMMENT(0)]]
        after you, from generation to generation. This is the everlasting covenant:
        I will always be your God and the God of your descendants after you. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>seed; </b>also in 17:7b, 8, 9, 10, 19.
    - title: The Mark of the Covenant
      content: "And I will give the entire land of Canaan, where you now live as
        a foreigner, to you and your descendants. It will be their possession forever,
        and I will be their God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said to Abraham, \u201CYour responsibility is to obey the
        terms of the covenant. You and all your descendants have this continual responsibility. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is the covenant that you and your descendants must keep: Each
        male among you must be circumcised. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You must cut off the flesh of your foreskin as a sign of the covenant
        between me and you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From generation to generation, every male child must be circumcised
        on the eighth day after his birth. This applies not only to members of your
        family but also to the servants born in your household and the foreign-born
        servants whom you have purchased. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'All must be circumcised. Your bodies will bear the mark of my everlasting
        covenant. '
      comments: []
    - title: Sarai Is Named Sarah
      content: "Any male who fails to be circumcised will be cut off from the covenant
        family for breaking the covenant.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said to Abraham, \u201CRegarding Sarai, your wife\u2014her
        name will no longer be Sarai. From now on her name will be Sarah.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '17:15 '
        content: "<b>Sarai </b>and <b>Sarah </b>both mean \u201Cprincess\u201D; the
          change in spelling may reflect the difference in dialect between Ur and
          Canaan."
    - title: 
      content: "And I will bless her and give you a son from her! Yes, I will bless
        her richly, and she will become the mother of many nations. Kings of nations
        will be among her descendants.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Abraham bowed down to the ground, but he laughed to himself
        in disbelief. \u201CHow could I become a father at the age of 100?\u201D
        he thought. \u201CAnd how can Sarah have a baby when she is ninety years
        old?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Abraham said to God, \u201CMay Ishmael live under your special
        blessing!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But God replied, \u201CNo\u2014Sarah, your wife, will give birth
        to a son for you. You will name him Isaac,[[COMMENT(0)]] and I will confirm
        my covenant with him and his descendants as an everlasting covenant. "
      comments:
      - number: '17:19 '
        content: "<b>Isaac </b>means \u201Che laughs.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'As for Ishmael, I will bless him also, just as you have asked. I
        will make him extremely fruitful and multiply his descendants. He will become
        the father of twelve princes, and I will make him a great nation. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But my covenant will be confirmed with Isaac, who will be born to
        you and Sarah about this time next year.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When God had finished speaking, he left Abraham.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On that very day Abraham took his son, Ishmael, and every male in
        his household, including those born there and those he had bought. Then he
        circumcised them, cutting off their foreskins, just as God had told him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abraham was ninety-nine years old when he was circumcised, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and Ishmael, his son, was thirteen. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Both Abraham and his son, Ishmael, were circumcised on that same
        day, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Son Is Promised to Sarah
      content: '  The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared again to Abraham near
        the oak grove belonging to Mamre. One day Abraham was sitting at the entrance
        to his tent during the hottest part of the day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He looked up and noticed three men standing nearby. When he saw them,
        he ran to meet them and welcomed them, bowing low to the ground.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMy lord,\u201D he said, \u201Cif it pleases you, stop here
        for a while. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Rest in the shade of this tree while water is brought to wash your
        feet. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And since you\u2019ve honored your servant with this visit, let me
        prepare some food to refresh you before you continue on your journey.\u201D\u201CAll
        right,\u201D they said. \u201CDo as you have said.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Abraham ran back to the tent and said to Sarah, \u201CHurry! Get
        three large measures[[COMMENT(0)]] of your best flour, knead it into dough,
        and bake some bread.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '18:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>3 seahs, </b>about half a bushel or 22 liters.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Abraham ran out to the herd and chose a tender calf and gave
        it to his servant, who quickly prepared it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the food was ready, Abraham took some yogurt and milk and the
        roasted meat, and he served it to the men. As they ate, Abraham waited on
        them in the shade of the trees.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhere is Sarah, your wife?\u201D the visitors asked.\u201CShe\u2019s
        inside the tent,\u201D Abraham replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then one of them said, \u201CI will return to you about this time
        next year, and your wife, Sarah, will have a son!\u201DSarah was listening
        to this conversation from the tent. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abraham and Sarah were both very old by this time, and Sarah was
        long past the age of having children. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So she laughed silently to herself and said, \u201CHow could a worn-out
        woman like me enjoy such pleasure, especially when my master\u2014my husband\u2014is
        also so old?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Abraham, \u201CWhy did
        Sarah laugh? Why did she say, \u2018Can an old woman like me have a baby?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Is anything too hard for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>? I will
        return about this time next year, and Sarah will have a son.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Abraham Intercedes for Sodom
      content: "Sarah was afraid, so she denied it, saying, \u201CI didn\u2019t laugh.\u201DBut
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said, \u201CNo, you did laugh.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the men got up from their meal and looked out toward Sodom.
        As they left, Abraham went with them to send them on their way.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CShould I hide my plan from Abraham?\u201D the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        asked. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor Abraham will certainly become a great and mighty nation,
        and all the nations of the earth will be blessed through him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have singled him out so that he will direct his sons and their
        families to keep the way of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> by doing what
        is right and just. Then I will do for Abraham all that I have promised.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told Abraham, \u201CI have heard
        a great outcry from Sodom and Gomorrah, because their sin is so flagrant. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I am going down to see if their actions are as wicked as I have heard.
        If not, I want to know.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The other men turned and headed toward Sodom, but the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        remained with Abraham. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abraham approached him and said, \u201CWill you sweep away both the
        righteous and the wicked? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Suppose you find fifty righteous people living there in the city\u2014will
        you still sweep it away and not spare it for their sakes? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Surely you wouldn\u2019t do such a thing, destroying the righteous
        along with the wicked. Why, you would be treating the righteous and the wicked
        exactly the same! Surely you wouldn\u2019t do that! Should not the Judge
        of all the earth do what is right?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CIf I find fifty
        righteous people in Sodom, I will spare the entire city for their sake.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Abraham spoke again. \u201CSince I have begun, let me speak
        further to my Lord, even though I am but dust and ashes. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Suppose there are only forty-five righteous people rather than fifty?
        Will you destroy the whole city for lack of five?\u201DAnd the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        said, \u201CI will not destroy it if I find forty-five righteous people there.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Abraham pressed his request further. \u201CSuppose there are
        only forty?\u201DAnd the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CI will
        not destroy it for the sake of the forty.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlease don\u2019t be angry, my Lord,\u201D Abraham pleaded.
        \u201CLet me speak\u2014suppose only thirty righteous people are found?\u201DAnd
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CI will not destroy it if I
        find thirty.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Abraham said, \u201CSince I have dared to speak to the Lord,
        let me continue\u2014suppose there are only twenty?\u201DAnd the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        replied, \u201CThen I will not destroy it for the sake of the twenty.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, Abraham said, \u201CLord, please don\u2019t be angry with
        me if I speak one more time. Suppose only ten are found there?\u201DAnd the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> replied, \u201CThen I will not destroy it for
        the sake of the ten.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Sodom and Gomorrah Destroyed
      content: '  That evening the two angels came to the entrance of the city of
        Sodom. Lot was sitting there, and when he saw them, he stood up to meet them.
        Then he welcomed them and bowed with his face to the ground. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMy lords,\u201D he said, \u201Ccome to my home to wash your
        feet, and be my guests for the night. You may then get up early in the morning
        and be on your way again.\u201D\u201COh no,\u201D they replied. \u201CWe\u2019ll
        just spend the night out here in the city square.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Lot insisted, so at last they went home with him. Lot prepared
        a feast for them, complete with fresh bread made without yeast, and they
        ate. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But before they retired for the night, all the men of Sodom, young
        and old, came from all over the city and surrounded the house. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They shouted to Lot, \u201CWhere are the men who came to spend the
        night with you? Bring them out to us so we can have sex with them!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Lot stepped outside to talk to them, shutting the door behind
        him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlease, my brothers,\u201D he begged, \u201Cdon\u2019t do such
        a wicked thing. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Look, I have two virgin daughters. Let me bring them out to you,
        and you can do with them as you wish. But please, leave these men alone,
        for they are my guests and are under my protection.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CStand back!\u201D they shouted. \u201CThis fellow came to town
        as an outsider, and now he\u2019s acting like our judge! We\u2019ll treat
        you far worse than those other men!\u201D And they lunged toward Lot to break
        down the door.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the two angels[[COMMENT(0)]] reached out, pulled Lot into the
        house, and bolted the door. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:10 '
        content: Hebrew <b>men; </b>also in 19:12, 16.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they blinded all the men, young and old, who were at the door
        of the house, so they gave up trying to get inside.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, the angels questioned Lot. \u201CDo you have any other
        relatives here in the city?\u201D they asked. \u201CGet them out of this
        place\u2014your sons-in-law, sons, daughters, or anyone else. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For we are about to destroy this city completely. The outcry against
        this place is so great it has reached the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, and
        he has sent us to destroy it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Lot rushed out to tell his daughters\u2019 fianc\xE9s, \u201CQuick,
        get out of the city! The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> is about to destroy
        it.\u201D But the young men thought he was only joking.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At dawn the next morning the angels became insistent. \u201CHurry,\u201D
        they said to Lot. \u201CTake your wife and your two daughters who are here.
        Get out right now, or you will be swept away in the destruction of the city!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Lot still hesitated, the angels seized his hand and the hands
        of his wife and two daughters and rushed them to safety outside the city,
        for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was merciful. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they were safely out of the city, one of the angels ordered,
        \u201CRun for your lives! And don\u2019t look back or stop anywhere in the
        valley! Escape to the mountains, or you will be swept away!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COh no, my lord!\u201D Lot begged. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou have been so gracious to me and saved my life, and you
        have shown such great kindness. But I cannot go to the mountains. Disaster
        would catch up to me there, and I would soon die. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "See, there is a small village nearby. Please let me go there instead;
        don\u2019t you see how small it is? Then my life will be saved.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D the angel said, \u201CI will grant your request.
        I will not destroy the little village. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But hurry! Escape to it, for I can do nothing until you arrive there.\u201D
        (This explains why that village was known as Zoar, which means \u201Clittle
        place.\u201D)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Lot reached the village just as the sun was rising over the horizon. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> rained down fire and burning
        sulfur from the sky on Sodom and Gomorrah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He utterly destroyed them, along with the other cities and villages
        of the plain, wiping out all the people and every bit of vegetation. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Lot\u2019s wife looked back as she was following behind him,
        and she turned into a pillar of salt.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abraham got up early that morning and hurried out to the place where
        he had stood in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He looked out across the plain toward Sodom and Gomorrah and watched
        as columns of smoke rose from the cities like smoke from a furnace.  '
      comments: []
    - title: Lot and His Daughters
      content: "But God had listened to Abraham\u2019s request and kept Lot safe,
        removing him from the disaster that engulfed the cities on the plain.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Afterward Lot left Zoar because he was afraid of the people there,
        and he went to live in a cave in the mountains with his two daughters. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day the older daughter said to her sister, \u201CThere are no
        men left anywhere in this entire area, so we can\u2019t get married like
        everyone else. And our father will soon be too old to have children. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Come, let\u2019s get him drunk with wine, and then we will have sex
        with him. That way we will preserve our family line through our father.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So that night they got him drunk with wine, and the older daughter
        went in and had intercourse with her father. He was unaware of her lying
        down or getting up again.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The next morning the older daughter said to her younger sister, \u201CI
        had sex with our father last night. Let\u2019s get him drunk with wine again
        tonight, and you go in and have sex with him. That way we will preserve our
        family line through our father.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So that night they got him drunk with wine again, and the younger
        daughter went in and had intercourse with him. As before, he was unaware
        of her lying down or getting up again.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As a result, both of Lot\u2019s daughters became pregnant by their
        own father. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the older daughter gave birth to a son, she named him Moab.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        He became the ancestor of the nation now known as the Moabites. '
      comments:
      - number: '19:37 '
        content: "<b>Moab </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Cfrom father.\u201D"
  - verses:
    - title: Abraham Deceives Abimelech
      content: '  Abraham moved south to the Negev and lived for a while between
        Kadesh and Shur, and then he moved on to Gerar. While living there as a foreigner, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abraham introduced his wife, Sarah, by saying, \u201CShe is my sister.\u201D
        So King Abimelech of Gerar sent for Sarah and had her brought to him at his
        palace.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But that night God came to Abimelech in a dream and told him, \u201CYou
        are a dead man, for that woman you have taken is already married!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Abimelech had not slept with her yet, so he said, \u201CLord,
        will you destroy an innocent nation? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Didn\u2019t Abraham tell me, \u2018She is my sister\u2019? And she
        herself said, \u2018Yes, he is my brother.\u2019 I acted in complete innocence!
        My hands are clean.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In the dream God responded, \u201CYes, I know you are innocent. That\u2019s
        why I kept you from sinning against me, and why I did not let you touch her. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now return the woman to her husband, and he will pray for you, for
        he is a prophet. Then you will live. But if you don\u2019t return her to
        him, you can be sure that you and all your people will die.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abimelech got up early the next morning and quickly called all his
        servants together. When he told them what had happened, his men were terrified. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Abimelech called for Abraham. \u201CWhat have you done to us?\u201D
        he demanded. \u201CWhat crime have I committed that deserves treatment like
        this, making me and my kingdom guilty of this great sin? No one should ever
        do what you have done! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Whatever possessed you to do such a thing?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abraham replied, \u201CI thought, \u2018This is a godless place.
        They will want my wife and will kill me to get her.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And she really is my sister, for we both have the same father, but
        different mothers. And I married her. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When God called me to leave my father\u2019s home and to travel from
        place to place, I told her, \u2018Do me a favor. Wherever we go, tell the
        people that I am your brother.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Abimelech took some of his sheep and goats, cattle, and male
        and female servants, and he presented them to Abraham. He also returned his
        wife, Sarah, to him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Abimelech said, \u201CLook over my land and choose any place
        where you would like to live.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And he said to Sarah, \u201CLook, I am giving your \u2018brother\u2019
        1,000 pieces of silver[[COMMENT(0)]] in the presence of all these witnesses.
        This is to compensate you for any wrong I may have done to you. This will
        settle any claim against me, and your reputation is cleared.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '20:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>1,000 [shekels] of silver, </b>about 25 pounds or 11.4
          kilograms in weight.
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Abraham prayed to God, and God healed Abimelech, his wife, and
        his female servants, so they could have children. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Birth of Isaac
      content: '  The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> kept his word and did for Sarah
        exactly what he had promised. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'She became pregnant, and she gave birth to a son for Abraham in his
        old age. This happened at just the time God had said it would. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And Abraham named their son Isaac. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eight days after Isaac was born, Abraham circumcised him as God had
        commanded. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abraham was 100 years old when Isaac was born.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Sarah declared, \u201CGod has brought me laughter.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        All who hear about this will laugh with me. "
      comments:
      - number: '21:6 '
        content: "The name <b>Isaac </b>means \u201Che laughs.\u201D"
    - title: Hagar and Ishmael Are Sent Away
      content: "Who would have said to Abraham that Sarah would nurse a baby? Yet
        I have given Abraham a son in his old age!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Isaac grew up and was about to be weaned, Abraham prepared a
        huge feast to celebrate the occasion. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Sarah saw Ishmael\u2014the son of Abraham and her Egyptian servant
        Hagar\u2014making fun of her son, Isaac.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:9 '
        content: As in Greek version and Latin Vulgate; Hebrew lacks <b>of her son,
          Isaac.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So she turned to Abraham and demanded, \u201CGet rid of that slave
        woman and her son. He is not going to share the inheritance with my son,
        Isaac. I won\u2019t have it!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This upset Abraham very much because Ishmael was his son. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But God told Abraham, \u201CDo not be upset over the boy and your
        servant. Do whatever Sarah tells you, for Isaac is the son through whom your
        descendants will be counted. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But I will also make a nation of the descendants of Hagar\u2019s
        son because he is your son, too.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Abraham got up early the next morning, prepared food and a container
        of water, and strapped them on Hagar\u2019s shoulders. Then he sent her away
        with their son, and she wandered aimlessly in the wilderness of Beersheba.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the water was gone, she put the boy in the shade of a bush. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then she went and sat down by herself about a hundred yards[[COMMENT(0)]]
        away. \u201CI don\u2019t want to watch the boy die,\u201D she said, as she
        burst into tears.  "
      comments:
      - number: '21:16 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a bowshot.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "But God heard the boy crying, and the angel of God called to Hagar
        from heaven, \u201CHagar, what\u2019s wrong? Do not be afraid! God has heard
        the boy crying as he lies there. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Go to him and comfort him, for I will make a great nation from his
        descendants.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God opened Hagar\u2019s eyes, and she saw a well full of water.
        She quickly filled her water container and gave the boy a drink.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And God was with the boy as he grew up in the wilderness. He became
        a skillful archer, '
      comments: []
    - title: "Abraham\u2019s Covenant with Abimelech"
      content: 'and he settled in the wilderness of Paran. His mother arranged for
        him to marry a woman from the land of Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "About this time, Abimelech came with Phicol, his army commander,
        to visit Abraham. \u201CGod is obviously with you, helping you in everything
        you do,\u201D Abimelech said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSwear to me in God\u2019s name that you will never deceive
        me, my children, or any of my descendants. I have been loyal to you, so now
        swear that you will be loyal to me and to this country where you are living
        as a foreigner.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abraham replied, \u201CYes, I swear to it!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Abraham complained to Abimelech about a well that Abimelech\u2019s
        servants had taken by force from Abraham\u2019s servants.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is the first I\u2019ve heard of it,\u201D Abimelech answered.
        \u201CI have no idea who is responsible. You have never complained about
        this before.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abraham then gave some of his sheep, goats, and cattle to Abimelech,
        and they made a treaty. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Abraham also took seven additional female lambs and set them
        off by themselves. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abimelech asked, \u201CWhy have you set these seven apart from the
        others?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abraham replied, \u201CPlease accept these seven lambs to show your
        agreement that I dug this well.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he named the place Beersheba (which means \u201Cwell of the
        oath\u201D), because that was where they had sworn the oath.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After making their covenant at Beersheba, Abimelech left with Phicol,
        the commander of his army, and they returned home to the land of the Philistines. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Abraham planted a tamarisk tree at Beersheba, and there he worshiped
        the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the Eternal God.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '21:33 '
        content: Hebrew <b>El-Olam.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: "Abraham\u2019s Faith Tested"
      content: "  Some time later, God tested Abraham\u2019s faith. \u201CAbraham!\u201D
        God called.\u201CYes,\u201D he replied. \u201CHere I am.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTake your son, your only son\u2014yes, Isaac, whom you love
        so much\u2014and go to the land of Moriah. Go and sacrifice him as a burnt
        offering on one of the mountains, which I will show you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next morning Abraham got up early. He saddled his donkey and
        took two of his servants with him, along with his son, Isaac. Then he chopped
        wood for a fire for a burnt offering and set out for the place God had told
        him about. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'On the third day of their journey, Abraham looked up and saw the
        place in the distance. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CStay here with the donkey,\u201D Abraham told the servants.
        \u201CThe boy and I will travel a little farther. We will worship there,
        and then we will come right back.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Abraham placed the wood for the burnt offering on Isaac\u2019s
        shoulders, while he himself carried the fire and the knife. As the two of
        them walked on together, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isaac turned to Abraham and said, \u201CFather?\u201D\u201CYes, my
        son?\u201D Abraham replied.\u201CWe have the fire and the wood,\u201D the
        boy said, \u201Cbut where is the sheep for the burnt offering?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGod will provide a sheep for the burnt offering, my son,\u201D
        Abraham answered. And they both walked on together.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When they arrived at the place where God had told him to go, Abraham
        built an altar and arranged the wood on it. Then he tied his son, Isaac,
        and laid him on the altar on top of the wood. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And Abraham picked up the knife to kill his son as a sacrifice. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At that moment the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> called
        to him from heaven, \u201CAbraham! Abraham!\u201D\u201CYes,\u201D Abraham
        replied. \u201CHere I am!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDon\u2019t lay a hand on the boy!\u201D the angel said. \u201CDo
        not hurt him in any way, for now I know that you truly fear God. You have
        not withheld from me even your son, your only son.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Abraham looked up and saw a ram caught by its horns in a thicket.
        So he took the ram and sacrificed it as a burnt offering in place of his
        son. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abraham named the place Yahweh-Yireh (which means \u201Cthe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will provide\u201D). To this day, people still use that name as a proverb:
        \u201COn the mountain of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> it will be provided.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the angel of the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> called again to
        Abraham from heaven. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> says: Because
        you have obeyed me and have not withheld even your son, your only son, I
        swear by my own name that "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I will certainly bless you. I will multiply your descendants[[COMMENT(0)]]
        beyond number, like the stars in the sky and the sand on the seashore. Your
        descendants will conquer the cities of their enemies. '
      comments:
      - number: '22:17 '
        content: Hebrew <b>seed; </b>also in 22:17b, 18.
    - title: 
      content: "And through your descendants all the nations of the earth will be
        blessed\u2014all because you have obeyed me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they returned to the servants and traveled back to Beersheba,
        where Abraham continued to live.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Soon after this, Abraham heard that Milcah, his brother Nahor\u2019s
        wife, had borne Nahor eight sons. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The oldest was named Uz, the next oldest was Buz, followed by Kemuel
        (the ancestor of the Arameans), '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Kesed, Hazo, Pildash, Jidlaph, and Bethuel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(Bethuel became the father of Rebekah.) In addition to these eight
        sons from Milcah, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Burial of Sarah
      content: '  When Sarah was 127 years old, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'she died at Kiriath-arba (now called Hebron) in the land of Canaan.
        There Abraham mourned and wept for her.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then, leaving her body, he said to the Hittite elders, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHere I am, a stranger and a foreigner among you. Please sell
        me a piece of land so I can give my wife a proper burial.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The Hittites replied to Abraham, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CListen, my lord, you are an honored prince among us. Choose
        the finest of our tombs and bury her there. No one here will refuse to help
        you in this way.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Abraham bowed low before the Hittites '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and said, \u201CSince you are willing to help me in this way, be
        so kind as to ask Ephron son of Zohar "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "to let me buy his cave at Machpelah, down at the end of his field.
        I will pay the full price in the presence of witnesses, so I will have a
        permanent burial place for my family.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ephron was sitting there among the others, and he answered Abraham
        as the others listened, speaking publicly before all the Hittite elders of
        the town. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo, my lord,\u201D he said to Abraham, \u201Cplease listen
        to me. I will give you the field and the cave. Here in the presence of my
        people, I give it to you. Go and bury your dead.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abraham again bowed low before the citizens of the land, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and he replied to Ephron as everyone listened. \u201CNo, listen to
        me. I will buy it from you. Let me pay the full price for the field so I
        can bury my dead there.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ephron answered Abraham, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMy lord, please listen to me. The land is worth 400 pieces[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of silver, but what is that between friends? Go ahead and bury your dead.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '23:15 '
        content: Hebrew <b>400 shekels, </b>about 10 pounds or 4.6 kilograms in weight;
          also in 23:16.
    - title: 
      content: "So Abraham agreed to Ephron\u2019s price and paid the amount he had
        suggested\u2014400 pieces of silver, weighed according to the market standard.
        The Hittite elders witnessed the transaction.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Abraham bought the plot of land belonging to Ephron at Machpelah,
        near Mamre. This included the field itself, the cave that was in it, and
        all the surrounding trees. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It was transferred to Abraham as his permanent possession in the
        presence of the Hittite elders at the city gate. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Abraham buried his wife, Sarah, there in Canaan, in the cave
        of Machpelah, near Mamre (also called Hebron). '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: A Wife for Isaac
      content: '  Abraham was now a very old man, and the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        had blessed him in every way. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One day Abraham said to his oldest servant, the man in charge of
        his household, \u201CTake an oath by putting your hand under my thigh. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Swear by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of heaven and earth,
        that you will not allow my son to marry one of these local Canaanite women. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Go instead to my homeland, to my relatives, and find a wife there
        for my son Isaac.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The servant asked, \u201CBut what if I can\u2019t find a young woman
        who is willing to travel so far from home? Should I then take Isaac there
        to live among your relatives in the land you came from?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo!\u201D Abraham responded. \u201CBe careful never to take
        my son there. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of heaven, who took
        me from my father\u2019s house and my native land, solemnly promised to give
        this land to my descendants.[[COMMENT(0)]] He will send his angel ahead of
        you, and he will see to it that you find a wife there for my son. "
      comments:
      - number: '24:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>seed; </b>also in 24:60.
    - title: 
      content: "If she is unwilling to come back with you, then you are free from
        this oath of mine. But under no circumstances are you to take my son there.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the servant took an oath by putting his hand under the thigh of
        his master, Abraham. He swore to follow Abraham\u2019s instructions. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he loaded ten of Abraham\u2019s camels with all kinds of expensive
        gifts from his master, and he traveled to distant Aram-naharaim. There he
        went to the town where Abraham\u2019s brother Nahor had settled. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He made the camels kneel beside a well just outside the town. It
        was evening, and the women were coming out to draw water.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CO <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of my master, Abraham,\u201D
        he prayed. \u201CPlease give me success today, and show unfailing love to
        my master, Abraham. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'See, I am standing here beside this spring, and the young women of
        the town are coming out to draw water. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is my request. I will ask one of them, \u2018Please give me
        a drink from your jug.\u2019 If she says, \u2018Yes, have a drink, and I
        will water your camels, too!\u2019\u2014let her be the one you have selected
        as Isaac\u2019s wife. This is how I will know that you have shown unfailing
        love to my master.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Before he had finished praying, he saw a young woman named Rebekah
        coming out with her water jug on her shoulder. She was the daughter of Bethuel,
        who was the son of Abraham\u2019s brother Nahor and his wife, Milcah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Rebekah was very beautiful and old enough to be married, but she
        was still a virgin. She went down to the spring, filled her jug, and came
        up again. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Running over to her, the servant said, \u201CPlease give me a little
        drink of water from your jug.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes, my lord,\u201D she answered, \u201Chave a drink.\u201D
        And she quickly lowered her jug from her shoulder and gave him a drink. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When she had given him a drink, she said, \u201CI\u2019ll draw water
        for your camels, too, until they have had enough to drink.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So she quickly emptied her jug into the watering trough and ran back
        to the well to draw water for all his camels.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The servant watched her in silence, wondering whether or not the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> had given him success in his mission. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then at last, when the camels had finished drinking, he took out
        a gold ring for her nose and two large gold bracelets[[COMMENT(0)]] for her
        wrists.  '
      comments:
      - number: '24:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a gold nose-ring weighing a beka </b>[0.2 ounces or 6
          grams] <b>and two gold bracelets weighing 10 [shekels] </b>[4 ounces or
          114 grams].
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhose daughter are you?\u201D he asked. \u201CAnd please tell
        me, would your father have any room to put us up for the night?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am the daughter of Bethuel,\u201D she replied. \u201CMy grandparents
        are Nahor and Milcah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Yes, we have plenty of straw and feed for the camels, and we have
        room for guests.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The man bowed low and worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPraise the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of my master,
        Abraham,\u201D he said. \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has shown unfailing
        love and faithfulness to my master, for he has led me straight to my master\u2019s
        relatives.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The young woman ran home to tell her family everything that had happened. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now Rebekah had a brother named Laban, who ran out to meet the man
        at the spring. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He had seen the nose-ring and the bracelets on his sister\u2019s
        wrists, and had heard Rebekah tell what the man had said. So he rushed out
        to the spring, where the man was still standing beside his camels. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Laban said to him, \u201CCome and stay with us, you who are blessed
        by the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>! Why are you standing here outside the
        town when I have a room all ready for you and a place prepared for the camels?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the man went home with Laban, and Laban unloaded the camels, gave
        him straw for their bedding, fed them, and provided water for the man and
        the camel drivers to wash their feet. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then food was served. But Abraham\u2019s servant said, \u201CI don\u2019t
        want to eat until I have told you why I have come.\u201D\u201CAll right,\u201D
        Laban said, \u201Ctell us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am Abraham\u2019s servant,\u201D he explained. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has greatly blessed my
        master; he has become a wealthy man. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has
        given him flocks of sheep and goats, herds of cattle, a fortune in silver
        and gold, and many male and female servants and camels and donkeys.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhen Sarah, my master\u2019s wife, was very old, she gave birth
        to my master\u2019s son, and my master has given him everything he owns. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And my master made me take an oath. He said, \u2018Do not allow my
        son to marry one of these local Canaanite women. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Go instead to my father\u2019s house, to my relatives, and find a
        wife there for my son.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut I said to my master, \u2018What if I can\u2019t find a
        young woman who is willing to go back with me?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He responded, \u2018The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, in whose presence
        I have lived, will send his angel with you and will make your mission successful.
        Yes, you must find a wife for my son from among my relatives, from my father\u2019s
        family. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then you will have fulfilled your obligation. But if you go to my
        relatives and they refuse to let her go with you, you will be free from my
        oath.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo today when I came to the spring, I prayed this prayer: \u2018O
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, God of my master, Abraham, please give me success
        on this mission. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "See, I am standing here beside this spring. This is my request. When
        a young woman comes to draw water, I will say to her, \u201CPlease give me
        a little drink of water from your jug.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If she says, \u201CYes, have a drink, and I will draw water for your
        camels, too,\u201D let her be the one you have selected to be the wife of
        my master\u2019s son.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBefore I had finished praying in my heart, I saw Rebekah coming
        out with her water jug on her shoulder. She went down to the spring and drew
        water. So I said to her, \u2018Please give me a drink.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She quickly lowered her jug from her shoulder and said, \u2018Yes,
        have a drink, and I will water your camels, too!\u2019 So I drank, and then
        she watered the camels.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen I asked, \u2018Whose daughter are you?\u2019 She replied,
        \u2018I am the daughter of Bethuel, and my grandparents are Nahor and Milcah.\u2019
        So I put the ring on her nose, and the bracelets on her wrists.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen I bowed low and worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        I praised the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of my master, Abraham,
        because he had led me straight to my master\u2019s niece to be his son\u2019s
        wife. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So tell me\u2014will you or won\u2019t you show unfailing love and
        faithfulness to my master? Please tell me yes or no, and then I\u2019ll know
        what to do next.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Laban and Bethuel replied, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has obviously brought you here, so there is nothing we can say. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Here is Rebekah; take her and go. Yes, let her be the wife of your
        master\u2019s son, as the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has directed.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Abraham\u2019s servant heard their answer, he bowed down to
        the ground and worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he brought out silver and gold jewelry and clothing and presented
        them to Rebekah. He also gave expensive presents to her brother and mother. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then they ate their meal, and the servant and the men with him stayed
        there overnight.But early the next morning, Abraham\u2019s servant said,
        \u201CSend me back to my master.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut we want Rebekah to stay with us at least ten days,\u201D
        her brother and mother said. \u201CThen she can go.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But he said, \u201CDon\u2019t delay me. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has made my mission successful; now send me back so I can return to my master.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWell,\u201D they said, \u201Cwe\u2019ll call Rebekah and ask
        her what she thinks.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they called Rebekah. \u201CAre you willing to go with this man?\u201D
        they asked her.And she replied, \u201CYes, I will go.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they said good-bye to Rebekah and sent her away with Abraham\u2019s
        servant and his men. The woman who had been Rebekah\u2019s childhood nurse
        went along with her. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They gave her this blessing as she parted:\u201COur sister, may you
        becomethe mother of many millions!May your descendants be strongand conquer
        the cities of their enemies.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Rebekah and her servant girls mounted the camels and followed
        the man. So Abraham\u2019s servant took Rebekah and went on his way.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, Isaac, whose home was in the Negev, had returned from
        Beer-lahai-roi. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One evening as he was walking and meditating in the fields, he looked
        up and saw the camels coming. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Rebekah looked up and saw Isaac, she quickly dismounted from
        her camel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWho is that man walking through the fields to meet us?\u201D
        she asked the servant.And he replied, \u201CIt is my master.\u201D So Rebekah
        covered her face with her veil. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the servant told Isaac everything he had done.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Death of Abraham
      content: '  Abraham married another wife, whose name was Keturah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'She gave birth to Zimran, Jokshan, Medan, Midian, Ishbak, and Shuah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jokshan was the father of Sheba and Dedan. Dedan\u2019s descendants
        were the Asshurites, Letushites, and Leummites. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Midian\u2019s sons were Ephah, Epher, Hanoch, Abida, and Eldaah.
        These were all descendants of Abraham through Keturah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abraham gave everything he owned to his son Isaac. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But before he died, he gave gifts to the sons of his concubines and
        sent them off to a land in the east, away from Isaac.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Abraham lived for 175 years, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he died at a ripe old age, having lived a long and satisfying
        life. He breathed his last and joined his ancestors in death. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'His sons Isaac and Ishmael buried him in the cave of Machpelah, near
        Mamre, in the field of Ephron son of Zohar the Hittite. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This was the field Abraham had purchased from the Hittites and where
        he had buried his wife Sarah. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Ishmael\u2019s Descendants"
      content: "After Abraham\u2019s death, God blessed his son Isaac, who settled
        near Beer-lahai-roi in the Negev.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is the account of the family of Ishmael, the son of Abraham
        through Hagar, Sarah\u2019s Egyptian servant. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Here is a list, by their names and clans, of Ishmael\u2019s descendants:
        The oldest was Nebaioth, followed by Kedar, Adbeel, Mibsam, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Mishma, Dumah, Massa, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hadad, Tema, Jetur, Naphish, and Kedemah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These twelve sons of Ishmael became the founders of twelve tribes
        named after them, listed according to the places they settled and camped. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Ishmael lived for 137 years. Then he breathed his last and joined
        his ancestors in death. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Births of Esau and Jacob
      content: "Ishmael\u2019s descendants occupied the region from Havilah to Shur,
        which is east of Egypt in the direction of Asshur. There they lived in open
        hostility toward all their relatives.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:18 '
        content: The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'This is the account of the family of Isaac, the son of Abraham. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Isaac was forty years old, he married Rebekah, the daughter
        of Bethuel the Aramean from Paddan-aram and the sister of Laban the Aramean.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isaac pleaded with the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> on behalf of his
        wife, because she was unable to have children. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        answered Isaac\u2019s prayer, and Rebekah became pregnant with twins. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the two children struggled with each other in her womb. So she
        went to ask the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> about it. \u201CWhy is this happening
        to me?\u201D she asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> told her, \u201CThe sons in your
        womb will become two nations. From the very beginning, the two nations will
        be rivals. One nation will be stronger than the other; and your older son
        will serve your younger son.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And when the time came to give birth, Rebekah discovered that she
        did indeed have twins! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The first one was very red at birth and covered with thick hair like
        a fur coat. So they named him Esau.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '25:25 '
        content: "<b>Esau </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Chair.\u201D"
    - title: Esau Sells His Birthright
      content: "Then the other twin was born with his hand grasping Esau\u2019s heel.
        So they named him Jacob.[[COMMENT(0)]] Isaac was sixty years old when the
        twins were born.  "
      comments:
      - number: '25:26 '
        content: "<b>Jacob </b>sounds like the Hebrew words for \u201Cheel\u201D
          and \u201Cdeceiver.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'As the boys grew up, Esau became a skillful hunter. He was an outdoorsman,
        but Jacob had a quiet temperament, preferring to stay at home. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Isaac loved Esau because he enjoyed eating the wild game Esau brought
        home, but Rebekah loved Jacob.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One day when Jacob was cooking some stew, Esau arrived home from
        the wilderness exhausted and hungry. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Esau said to Jacob, \u201CI\u2019m starved! Give me some of that
        red stew!\u201D (This is how Esau got his other name, Edom, which means \u201Cred.\u201D)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D Jacob replied, \u201Cbut trade me your rights
        as the firstborn son.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLook, I\u2019m dying of starvation!\u201D said Esau. \u201CWhat
        good is my birthright to me now?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Jacob said, \u201CFirst you must swear that your birthright is
        mine.\u201D So Esau swore an oath, thereby selling all his rights as the
        firstborn to his brother, Jacob.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Isaac Deceives Abimelech
      content: "  A severe famine now struck the land, as had happened before in
        Abraham\u2019s time. So Isaac moved to Gerar, where Abimelech, king of the
        Philistines, lived.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared to Isaac and said, \u201CDo
        not go down to Egypt, but do as I tell you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Live here as a foreigner in this land, and I will be with you and
        bless you. I hereby confirm that I will give all these lands to you and your
        descendants,[[COMMENT(0)]] just as I solemnly promised Abraham, your father. '
      comments:
      - number: '26:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>seed; </b>also in 26:4, 24.
    - title: 
      content: 'I will cause your descendants to become as numerous as the stars
        of the sky, and I will give them all these lands. And through your descendants
        all the nations of the earth will be blessed. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will do this because Abraham listened to me and obeyed all my requirements,
        commands, decrees, and instructions.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Isaac stayed in Gerar.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the men who lived there asked Isaac about his wife, Rebekah,
        he said, \u201CShe is my sister.\u201D He was afraid to say, \u201CShe is
        my wife.\u201D He thought, \u201CThey will kill me to get her, because she
        is so beautiful.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But some time later, Abimelech, king of the Philistines, looked out
        his window and saw Isaac caressing Rebekah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Immediately, Abimelech called for Isaac and exclaimed, \u201CShe
        is obviously your wife! Why did you say, \u2018She is my sister\u2019?\u201D\u201CBecause
        I was afraid someone would kill me to get her from me,\u201D Isaac replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHow could you do this to us?\u201D Abimelech exclaimed. \u201COne
        of my people might easily have taken your wife and slept with her, and you
        would have made us guilty of great sin.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Conflict over Water Rights
      content: "Then Abimelech issued a public proclamation: \u201CAnyone who touches
        this man or his wife will be put to death!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Isaac planted his crops that year, he harvested a hundred times
        more grain than he planted, for the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> blessed him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He became a very rich man, and his wealth continued to grow. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He acquired so many flocks of sheep and goats, herds of cattle, and
        servants that the Philistines became jealous of him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the Philistines filled up all of Isaac\u2019s wells with dirt.
        These were the wells that had been dug by the servants of his father, Abraham.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, Abimelech ordered Isaac to leave the country. \u201CGo somewhere
        else,\u201D he said, \u201Cfor you have become too powerful for us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Isaac moved away to the Gerar Valley, where he set up their tents
        and settled down. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He reopened the wells his father had dug, which the Philistines had
        filled in after Abraham\u2019s death. Isaac also restored the names Abraham
        had given them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isaac\u2019s servants also dug in the Gerar Valley and discovered
        a well of fresh water. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But then the shepherds from Gerar came and claimed the spring. \u201CThis
        is our water,\u201D they said, and they argued over it with Isaac\u2019s
        herdsmen. So Isaac named the well Esek (which means \u201Cargument\u201D). "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isaac\u2019s men then dug another well, but again there was a dispute
        over it. So Isaac named it Sitnah (which means \u201Chostility\u201D). "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Abandoning that one, Isaac moved on and dug another well. This time
        there was no dispute over it, so Isaac named the place Rehoboth (which means
        \u201Copen space\u201D), for he said, \u201CAt last the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        has created enough space for us to prosper in this land.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'From there Isaac moved to Beersheba, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "where the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> appeared to him on the night
        of his arrival. \u201CI am the God of your father, Abraham,\u201D he said.
        \u201CDo not be afraid, for I am with you and will bless you. I will multiply
        your descendants, and they will become a great nation. I will do this because
        of my promise to Abraham, my servant.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: "Isaac\u2019s Covenant with Abimelech"
      content: 'Then Isaac built an altar there and worshiped the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>.
        He set up his camp at that place, and his servants dug another well.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One day King Abimelech came from Gerar with his adviser, Ahuzzath,
        and also Phicol, his army commander. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy have you come here?\u201D Isaac asked. \u201CYou obviously
        hate me, since you kicked me off your land.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They replied, \u201CWe can plainly see that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is with you. So we want to enter into a sworn treaty with you. Let\u2019s
        make a covenant. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Swear that you will not harm us, just as we have never troubled you.
        We have always treated you well, and we sent you away from us in peace. And
        now look how the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has blessed you!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Isaac prepared a covenant feast to celebrate the treaty, and they
        ate and drank together. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Early the next morning, they each took a solemn oath not to interfere
        with each other. Then Isaac sent them home again, and they left him in peace.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "That very day Isaac\u2019s servants came and told him about a new
        well they had dug. \u201CWe\u2019ve found water!\u201D they exclaimed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Isaac named the well Shibah (which means \u201Coath\u201D). And
        to this day the town that grew up there is called Beersheba (which means
        \u201Cwell of the oath\u201D).  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At the age of forty, Esau married two Hittite wives: Judith, the
        daughter of Beeri, and Basemath, the daughter of Elon. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Jacob Steals Esau\u2019s Blessing"
      content: "  One day when Isaac was old and turning blind, he called for Esau,
        his older son, and said, \u201CMy son.\u201D\u201CYes, Father?\u201D Esau
        replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am an old man now,\u201D Isaac said, \u201Cand I don\u2019t
        know when I may die. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Take your bow and a quiver full of arrows, and go out into the open
        country to hunt some wild game for me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Prepare my favorite dish, and bring it here for me to eat. Then I
        will pronounce the blessing that belongs to you, my firstborn son, before
        I die.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Rebekah overheard what Isaac had said to his son Esau. So when
        Esau left to hunt for the wild game, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "she said to her son Jacob, \u201CListen. I overheard your father
        say to Esau, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u2018Bring me some wild game and prepare me a delicious meal. Then
        I will bless you in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s presence before
        I die.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now, my son, listen to me. Do exactly as I tell you. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Go out to the flocks, and bring me two fine young goats. I\u2019ll
        use them to prepare your father\u2019s favorite dish. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then take the food to your father so he can eat it and bless you
        before he dies.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut look,\u201D Jacob replied to Rebekah, \u201Cmy brother,
        Esau, is a hairy man, and my skin is smooth. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What if my father touches me? He\u2019ll see that I\u2019m trying
        to trick him, and then he\u2019ll curse me instead of blessing me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But his mother replied, \u201CThen let the curse fall on me, my son!
        Just do what I tell you. Go out and get the goats for me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob went out and got the young goats for his mother. Rebekah
        took them and prepared a delicious meal, just the way Isaac liked it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then she took Esau\u2019s favorite clothes, which were there in the
        house, and gave them to her younger son, Jacob. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'She covered his arms and the smooth part of his neck with the skin
        of the young goats. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then she gave Jacob the delicious meal, including freshly baked bread.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jacob took the food to his father. \u201CMy father?\u201D he said.\u201CYes,
        my son,\u201D Isaac answered. \u201CWho are you\u2014Esau or Jacob?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob replied, \u201CIt\u2019s Esau, your firstborn son. I\u2019ve
        done as you told me. Here is the wild game. Now sit up and eat it so you
        can give me your blessing.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isaac asked, \u201CHow did you find it so quickly, my son?\u201D\u201CThe
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> your God put it in my path!\u201D Jacob replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Isaac said to Jacob, \u201CCome closer so I can touch you and
        make sure that you really are Esau.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jacob went closer to his father, and Isaac touched him. \u201CThe
        voice is Jacob\u2019s, but the hands are Esau\u2019s,\u201D Isaac said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But he did not recognize Jacob, because Jacob\u2019s hands felt hairy
        just like Esau\u2019s. So Isaac prepared to bless Jacob. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut are you really my son Esau?\u201D he asked.\u201CYes, I
        am,\u201D Jacob replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Isaac said, \u201CNow, my son, bring me the wild game. Let me
        eat it, and then I will give you my blessing.\u201D So Jacob took the food
        to his father, and Isaac ate it. He also drank the wine that Jacob served
        him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Isaac said to Jacob, \u201CPlease come a little closer and kiss
        me, my son.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jacob went over and kissed him. And when Isaac caught the smell
        of his clothes, he was finally convinced, and he blessed his son. He said,
        \u201CAh! The smell of my son is like the smell of the outdoors, which the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has blessed!  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFrom the dew of heavenand the richness of the earth,may God
        always give you abundant harvests of grainand bountiful new wine.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "May many nations become your servants,and may they bow down to you.May
        you be the master over your brothers,and may your mother\u2019s sons bow
        down to you.All who curse you will be cursed,and all who bless you will be
        blessed.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as Isaac had finished blessing Jacob, and almost before Jacob
        had left his father, Esau returned from his hunt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Esau prepared a delicious meal and brought it to his father. Then
        he said, \u201CSit up, my father, and eat my wild game so you can give me
        your blessing.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Isaac asked him, \u201CWho are you?\u201DEsau replied, \u201CIt\u2019s
        your son, your firstborn son, Esau.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Isaac began to tremble uncontrollably and said, \u201CThen who just
        served me wild game? I have already eaten it, and I blessed him just before
        you came. And yes, that blessing must stand!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Esau heard his father\u2019s words, he let out a loud and bitter
        cry. \u201COh my father, what about me? Bless me, too!\u201D he begged.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Isaac said, \u201CYour brother was here, and he tricked me. He
        has taken away your blessing.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Esau exclaimed, \u201CNo wonder his name is Jacob, for now he has
        cheated me twice.[[COMMENT(0)]] First he took my rights as the firstborn,
        and now he has stolen my blessing. Oh, haven\u2019t you saved even one blessing
        for me?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '27:36 '
        content: "<b>Jacob </b>sounds like the Hebrew words for \u201Cheel\u201D
          and \u201Cdeceiver.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "Isaac said to Esau, \u201CI have made Jacob your master and have
        declared that all his brothers will be his servants. I have guaranteed him
        an abundance of grain and wine\u2014what is left for me to give you, my son?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Esau pleaded, \u201CBut do you have only one blessing? Oh my father,
        bless me, too!\u201D Then Esau broke down and wept.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, his father, Isaac, said to him,\u201CYou will live away
        from the richness of the earth,and away from the dew of the heaven above.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Jacob Flees to Paddan-Aram
      content: "You will live by your sword,and you will serve your brother.But when
        you decide to break free,you will shake his yoke from your neck.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "From that time on, Esau hated Jacob because their father had given
        Jacob the blessing. And Esau began to scheme: \u201CI will soon be mourning
        my father\u2019s death. Then I will kill my brother, Jacob.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Rebekah heard about Esau\u2019s plans. So she sent for Jacob
        and told him, \u201CListen, Esau is consoling himself by plotting to kill
        you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So listen carefully, my son. Get ready and flee to my brother, Laban,
        in Haran. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Stay there with him until your brother cools off. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When he calms down and forgets what you have done to him, I will
        send for you to come back. Why should I lose both of you in one day?\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "  So Isaac called for Jacob, blessed him, and said, \u201CYou must
        not marry any of these Canaanite women. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Instead, go at once to Paddan-aram, to the house of your grandfather
        Bethuel, and marry one of your uncle Laban\u2019s daughters. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'May God Almighty[[COMMENT(0)]] bless you and give you many children.
        And may your descendants multiply and become many nations! '
      comments:
      - number: '28:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>El-Shaddai.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "May God pass on to you and your descendants[[COMMENT(0)]] the blessings
        he promised to Abraham. May you own this land where you are now living as
        a foreigner, for God gave this land to Abraham.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '28:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>seed; </b>also in 28:13, 14.
    - title: 
      content: "So Isaac sent Jacob away, and he went to Paddan-aram to stay with
        his uncle Laban, his mother\u2019s brother, the son of Bethuel the Aramean.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Esau knew that his father, Isaac, had blessed Jacob and sent him
        to Paddan-aram to find a wife, and that he had warned Jacob, \u201CYou must
        not marry a Canaanite woman.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also knew that Jacob had obeyed his parents and gone to Paddan-aram. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It was now very clear to Esau that his father did not like the local
        Canaanite women. '
      comments: []
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Dream at Bethel"
      content: "So Esau visited his uncle Ishmael\u2019s family and married one of
        Ishmael\u2019s daughters, in addition to the wives he already had. His new
        wife\u2019s name was Mahalath. She was the sister of Nebaioth and the daughter
        of Ishmael, Abraham\u2019s son.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, Jacob left Beersheba and traveled toward Haran. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'At sundown he arrived at a good place to set up camp and stopped
        there for the night. Jacob found a stone to rest his head against and lay
        down to sleep. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As he slept, he dreamed of a stairway that reached from the earth
        up to heaven. And he saw the angels of God going up and down the stairway.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At the top of the stairway stood the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>,
        and he said, \u201CI am the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, the God of your
        grandfather Abraham, and the God of your father, Isaac. The ground you are
        lying on belongs to you. I am giving it to you and your descendants. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Your descendants will be as numerous as the dust of the earth! They
        will spread out in all directions\u2014to the west and the east, to the north
        and the south. And all the families of the earth will be blessed through
        you and your descendants. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "What\u2019s more, I am with you, and I will protect you wherever
        you go. One day I will bring you back to this land. I will not leave you
        until I have finished giving you everything I have promised you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob awoke from his sleep and said, \u201CSurely the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        is in this place, and I wasn\u2019t even aware of it!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But he was also afraid and said, \u201CWhat an awesome place this
        is! It is none other than the house of God, the very gateway to heaven!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next morning Jacob got up very early. He took the stone he had
        rested his head against, and he set it upright as a memorial pillar. Then
        he poured olive oil over it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He named that place Bethel (which means \u201Chouse of God\u201D),
        although it was previously called Luz.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob made this vow: \u201CIf God will indeed be with me and
        protect me on this journey, and if he will provide me with food and clothing, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and if I return safely to my father\u2019s home, then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        will certainly be my God. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Jacob Arrives at Paddan-Aram
      content: '  Then Jacob hurried on, finally arriving in the land of the east. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He saw a well in the distance. Three flocks of sheep and goats lay
        in an open field beside it, waiting to be watered. But a heavy stone covered
        the mouth of the well.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'It was the custom there to wait for all the flocks to arrive before
        removing the stone and watering the animals. Afterward the stone would be
        placed back over the mouth of the well. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob went over to the shepherds and asked, \u201CWhere are you from,
        my friends?\u201D\u201CWe are from Haran,\u201D they answered.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDo you know a man there named Laban, the grandson of Nahor?\u201D
        he asked.\u201CYes, we do,\u201D they replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIs he doing well?\u201D Jacob asked.\u201CYes, he\u2019s well,\u201D
        they answered. \u201CLook, here comes his daughter Rachel with the flock
        now.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob said, \u201CLook, it\u2019s still broad daylight\u2014too early
        to round up the animals. Why don\u2019t you water the sheep and goats so
        they can get back out to pasture?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe can\u2019t water the animals until all the flocks have arrived,\u201D
        they replied. \u201CThen the shepherds move the stone from the mouth of the
        well, and we water all the sheep and goats.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob was still talking with them when Rachel arrived with her father\u2019s
        flock, for she was a shepherd. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And because Rachel was his cousin\u2014the daughter of Laban, his
        mother\u2019s brother\u2014and because the sheep and goats belonged to his
        uncle Laban, Jacob went over to the well and moved the stone from its mouth
        and watered his uncle\u2019s flock. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jacob kissed Rachel, and he wept aloud. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He explained to Rachel that he was her cousin on her father\u2019s
        side\u2014the son of her aunt Rebekah. So Rachel quickly ran and told her
        father, Laban.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As soon as Laban heard that his nephew Jacob had arrived, he ran
        out to meet him. He embraced and kissed him and brought him home. When Jacob
        had told him his story, '
      comments: []
    - title: Jacob Marries Leah and Rachel
      content: "Laban exclaimed, \u201CYou really are my own flesh and blood!\u201DAfter
        Jacob had stayed with Laban for about a month, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Laban said to him, \u201CYou shouldn\u2019t work for me without pay
        just because we are relatives. Tell me how much your wages should be.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now Laban had two daughters. The older daughter was named Leah, and
        the younger one was Rachel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "There was no sparkle in Leah\u2019s eyes,[[COMMENT(0)]] but Rachel
        had a beautiful figure and a lovely face. "
      comments:
      - number: '29:17 '
        content: Or <b>Leah had dull eyes, </b>or <b>Leah had soft eyes. </b>The
          meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "Since Jacob was in love with Rachel, he told her father, \u201CI\u2019ll
        work for you for seven years if you\u2019ll give me Rachel, your younger
        daughter, as my wife.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAgreed!\u201D Laban replied. \u201CI\u2019d rather give her
        to you than to anyone else. Stay and work with me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob worked seven years to pay for Rachel. But his love for her
        was so strong that it seemed to him but a few days.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, the time came for him to marry her. \u201CI have fulfilled
        my agreement,\u201D Jacob said to Laban. \u201CNow give me my wife so I can
        sleep with her.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Laban invited everyone in the neighborhood and prepared a wedding
        feast. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But that night, when it was dark, Laban took Leah to Jacob, and he
        slept with her. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(Laban had given Leah a servant, Zilpah, to be her maid.)  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when Jacob woke up in the morning\u2014it was Leah! \u201CWhat
        have you done to me?\u201D Jacob raged at Laban. \u201CI worked seven years
        for Rachel! Why have you tricked me?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIt\u2019s not our custom here to marry off a younger daughter
        ahead of the firstborn,\u201D Laban replied. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBut wait until the bridal week is over; then we\u2019ll give
        you Rachel, too\u2014provided you promise to work another seven years for
        me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob agreed to work seven more years. A week after Jacob had
        married Leah, Laban gave him Rachel, too. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '(Laban gave Rachel a servant, Bilhah, to be her maid.) '
      comments: []
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Many Children"
      content: 'So Jacob slept with Rachel, too, and he loved her much more than
        Leah. He then stayed and worked for Laban the additional seven years.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> saw that Leah was unloved, he
        enabled her to have children, but Rachel could not conceive. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Leah became pregnant and gave birth to a son. She named him Reuben,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        for she said, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has noticed my misery,
        and now my husband will love me.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '29:32 '
        content: "<b>Reuben </b>means \u201CLook, a son!\u201D It also sounds like
          the Hebrew for \u201CHe has seen my misery.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "She soon became pregnant again and gave birth to another son. She
        named him Simeon,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CThe <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        heard that I was unloved and has given me another son.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '29:33 '
        content: "<b>Simeon </b>probably means \u201Cone who hears.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "Then she became pregnant a third time and gave birth to another son.
        He was named Levi,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CSurely this time my
        husband will feel affection for me, since I have given him three sons!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '29:34 '
        content: "<b>Levi </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Cbeing attached\u201D
          or \u201Cfeeling affection for.\u201D"
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: "  When Rachel saw that she wasn\u2019t having any children for Jacob,
        she became jealous of her sister. She pleaded with Jacob, \u201CGive me children,
        or I\u2019ll die!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob became furious with Rachel. \u201CAm I God?\u201D he asked.
        \u201CHe\u2019s the one who has kept you from having children!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Rachel told him, \u201CTake my maid, Bilhah, and sleep with
        her. She will bear children for me,[[COMMENT(0)]] and through her I can have
        a family, too.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '30:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>bear children on my knees.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'So Rachel gave her servant, Bilhah, to Jacob as a wife, and he slept
        with her. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Bilhah became pregnant and presented him with a son. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Rachel named him Dan,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CGod has vindicated
        me! He has heard my request and given me a son.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '30:6 '
        content: "<b>Dan </b>means \u201Che judged\u201D or \u201Che vindicated.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Bilhah became pregnant again and gave Jacob a second son. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Rachel named him Naphtali,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CI have
        struggled hard with my sister, and I\u2019m winning!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:8 '
        content: "<b>Naphtali </b>means \u201Cmy struggle.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, Leah realized that she wasn\u2019t getting pregnant anymore,
        so she took her servant, Zilpah, and gave her to Jacob as a wife. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Soon Zilpah presented him with a son. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Leah named him Gad,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CHow fortunate
        I am!\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '30:11 '
        content: "<b>Gad </b>means \u201Cgood fortune.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Zilpah gave Jacob a second son. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Leah named him Asher,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CWhat
        joy is mine! Now the other women will celebrate with me.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:13 '
        content: "<b>Asher </b>means \u201Chappy.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "One day during the wheat harvest, Reuben found some mandrakes growing
        in a field and brought them to his mother, Leah. Rachel begged Leah, \u201CPlease
        give me some of your son\u2019s mandrakes.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Leah angrily replied, \u201CWasn\u2019t it enough that you stole
        my husband? Now will you steal my son\u2019s mandrakes, too?\u201DRachel
        answered, \u201CI will let Jacob sleep with you tonight if you give me some
        of the mandrakes.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So that evening, as Jacob was coming home from the fields, Leah went
        out to meet him. \u201CYou must come and sleep with me tonight!\u201D she
        said. \u201CI have paid for you with some mandrakes that my son found.\u201D
        So that night he slept with Leah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And God answered Leah\u2019s prayers. She became pregnant again and
        gave birth to a fifth son for Jacob. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She named him Issachar,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CGod has
        rewarded me for giving my servant to my husband as a wife.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '30:18 '
        content: "<b>Issachar </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Creward.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Leah became pregnant again and gave birth to a sixth son for
        Jacob. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She named him Zebulun,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CGod has
        given me a good reward. Now my husband will treat me with respect, for I
        have given him six sons.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '30:20 '
        content: "<b>Zebulun </b>probably means \u201Chonor.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Later she gave birth to a daughter and named her Dinah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then God remembered Rachel\u2019s plight and answered her prayers
        by enabling her to have children. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She became pregnant and gave birth to a son. \u201CGod has removed
        my disgrace,\u201D she said. "
      comments: []
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Wealth Increases"
      content: "And she named him Joseph,[[COMMENT(0)]] for she said, \u201CMay the
        <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> add yet another son to my family.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '30:24 '
        content: "<b>Joseph </b>means \u201Cmay he add.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "Soon after Rachel had given birth to Joseph, Jacob said to Laban,
        \u201CPlease release me so I can go home to my own country. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Let me take my wives and children, for I have earned them by serving
        you, and let me be on my way. You certainly know how hard I have worked for
        you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlease listen to me,\u201D Laban replied. \u201CI have become
        wealthy, for[[COMMENT(0)]] the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has blessed me
        because of you. "
      comments:
      - number: '30:27 '
        content: Or <b>I have learned by divination that.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Tell me how much I owe you. Whatever it is, I\u2019ll pay it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob replied, \u201CYou know how hard I\u2019ve worked for you,
        and how your flocks and herds have grown under my care. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You had little indeed before I came, but your wealth has increased
        enormously. The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> has blessed you through everything
        I\u2019ve done. But now, what about me? When can I start providing for my
        own family?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat wages do you want?\u201D Laban asked again.Jacob replied,
        \u201CDon\u2019t give me anything. Just do this one thing, and I\u2019ll
        continue to tend and watch over your flocks. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Let me inspect your flocks today and remove all the sheep and goats
        that are speckled or spotted, along with all the black sheep. Give these
        to me as my wages. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In the future, when you check on the animals you have given me as
        my wages, you\u2019ll see that I have been honest. If you find in my flock
        any goats without speckles or spots, or any sheep that are not black, you
        will know that I have stolen them from you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D Laban replied. \u201CIt will be as you say.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But that very day Laban went out and removed the male goats that
        were streaked and spotted, all the female goats that were speckled and spotted
        or had white patches, and all the black sheep. He placed them in the care
        of his own sons, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "who took them a three-days\u2019 journey from where Jacob was. Meanwhile,
        Jacob stayed and cared for the rest of Laban\u2019s flock.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jacob took some fresh branches from poplar, almond, and plane
        trees and peeled off strips of bark, making white streaks on them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he placed these peeled branches in the watering troughs where
        the flocks came to drink, for that was where they mated. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And when they mated in front of the white-streaked branches, they
        gave birth to young that were streaked, speckled, and spotted. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob separated those lambs from Laban\u2019s flock. And at mating
        time he turned the flock to face Laban\u2019s animals that were streaked
        or black. This is how he built his own flock instead of increasing Laban\u2019s.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Whenever the stronger females were ready to mate, Jacob would place
        the peeled branches in the watering troughs in front of them. Then they would
        mate in front of the branches. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But he didn\u2019t do this with the weaker ones, so the weaker lambs
        belonged to Laban, and the stronger ones were Jacob\u2019s. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Jacob Flees from Laban
      content: "  But Jacob soon learned that Laban\u2019s sons were grumbling about
        him. \u201CJacob has robbed our father of everything!\u201D they said. \u201CHe
        has gained all his wealth at our father\u2019s expense.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Jacob began to notice a change in Laban\u2019s attitude toward
        him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> said to Jacob, \u201CReturn
        to the land of your father and grandfather and to your relatives there, and
        I will be with you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob called Rachel and Leah out to the field where he was watching
        his flock. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said to them, \u201CI have noticed that your father\u2019s attitude
        toward me has changed. But the God of my father has been with me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You know how hard I have worked for your father, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'but he has cheated me, changing my wages ten times. But God has not
        allowed him to do me any harm. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For if he said, \u2018The speckled animals will be your wages,\u2019
        the whole flock began to produce speckled young. And when he changed his
        mind and said, \u2018The striped animals will be your wages,\u2019 then the
        whole flock produced striped young. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In this way, God has taken your father\u2019s animals and given them
        to me.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201COne time during the mating season, I had a dream and saw that
        the male goats mating with the females were streaked, speckled, and spotted. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then in my dream, the angel of God said to me, \u2018Jacob!\u2019
        And I replied, \u2018Yes, here I am.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe angel said, \u2018Look up, and you will see that only the
        streaked, speckled, and spotted males are mating with the females of your
        flock. For I have seen how Laban has treated you. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I am the God who appeared to you at Bethel,[[COMMENT(0)]] the place
        where you anointed the pillar of stone and made your vow to me. Now get ready
        and leave this country and return to the land of your birth.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '31:13 '
        content: As in Greek version and an Aramaic Targum; Hebrew reads <b>the God
          of Bethel.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Rachel and Leah responded, \u201CThat\u2019s fine with us! We won\u2019t
        inherit any of our father\u2019s wealth anyway. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He has reduced our rights to those of foreign women. And after he
        sold us, he wasted the money you paid him for us. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "All the wealth God has given you from our father legally belongs
        to us and our children. So go ahead and do whatever God has told you.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob put his wives and children on camels, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he drove all his livestock in front of him. He packed all the
        belongings he had acquired in Paddan-aram and set out for the land of Canaan,
        where his father, Isaac, lived. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "At the time they left, Laban was some distance away, shearing his
        sheep. Rachel stole her father\u2019s household idols and took them with
        her. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jacob outwitted Laban the Aramean, for they set out secretly and
        never told Laban they were leaving. '
      comments: []
    - title: Laban Pursues Jacob
      content: 'So Jacob took all his possessions with him and crossed the Euphrates
        River,[[COMMENT(0)]] heading for the hill country of Gilead.  '
      comments:
      - number: '31:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>the river.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Three days later, Laban was told that Jacob had fled. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So he gathered a group of his relatives and set out in hot pursuit.
        He caught up with Jacob seven days later in the hill country of Gilead. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the previous night God had appeared to Laban the Aramean in a
        dream and told him, \u201CI\u2019m warning you\u2014leave Jacob alone!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Laban caught up with Jacob as he was camped in the hill country of
        Gilead, and he set up his camp not far from Jacob\u2019s. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat do you mean by deceiving me like this?\u201D Laban demanded.
        \u201CHow dare you drag my daughters away like prisoners of war? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why did you slip away secretly? Why did you deceive me? And why didn\u2019t
        you say you wanted to leave? I would have given you a farewell feast, with
        singing and music, accompanied by tambourines and harps. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why didn\u2019t you let me kiss my daughters and grandchildren and
        tell them good-bye? You have acted very foolishly! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I could destroy you, but the God of your father appeared to me last
        night and warned me, \u2018Leave Jacob alone!\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I can understand your feeling that you must go, and your intense
        longing for your father\u2019s home. But why have you stolen my gods?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI rushed away because I was afraid,\u201D Jacob answered. \u201CI
        thought you would take your daughters from me by force. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But as for your gods, see if you can find them, and let the person
        who has taken them die! And if you find anything else that belongs to you,
        identify it before all these relatives of ours, and I will give it back!\u201D
        But Jacob did not know that Rachel had stolen the household idols.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Laban went first into Jacob\u2019s tent to search there, then into
        Leah\u2019s, and then the tents of the two servant wives\u2014but he found
        nothing. Finally, he went into Rachel\u2019s tent. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Rachel had taken the household idols and hidden them in her camel
        saddle, and now she was sitting on them. When Laban had thoroughly searched
        her tent without finding them, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "she said to her father, \u201CPlease, sir, forgive me if I don\u2019t
        get up for you. I\u2019m having my monthly period.\u201D So Laban continued
        his search, but he could not find the household idols.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob became very angry, and he challenged Laban. \u201CWhat\u2019s
        my crime?\u201D he demanded. \u201CWhat have I done wrong to make you chase
        after me as though I were a criminal? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You have rummaged through everything I own. Now show me what you
        found that belongs to you! Set it out here in front of us, before our relatives,
        for all to see. Let them judge between us!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CFor twenty years I have been with you, caring for your flocks.
        In all that time your sheep and goats never miscarried. In all those years
        I never used a single ram of yours for food. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If any were attacked and killed by wild animals, I never showed you
        the carcass and asked you to reduce the count of your flock. No, I took the
        loss myself! You made me pay for every stolen animal, whether it was taken
        in broad daylight or in the dark of night.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI worked for you through the scorching heat of the day and
        through cold and sleepless nights. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Yes, for twenty years I slaved in your house! I worked for fourteen
        years earning your two daughters, and then six more years for your flock.
        And you changed my wages ten times! '
      comments: []
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Treaty with Laban"
      content: "In fact, if the God of my father had not been on my side\u2014the
        God of Abraham and the fearsome God of Isaac[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2014you would
        have sent me away empty-handed. But God has seen your abuse and my hard work.
        That is why he appeared to you last night and rebuked you!\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '31:42 '
        content: Or <b>and the Fear of Isaac.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Then Laban replied to Jacob, \u201CThese women are my daughters,
        these children are my grandchildren, and these flocks are my flocks\u2014in
        fact, everything you see is mine. But what can I do now about my daughters
        and their children? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So come, let\u2019s make a covenant, you and I, and it will be a
        witness to our commitment.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob took a stone and set it up as a monument. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he told his family members, \u201CGather some stones.\u201D
        So they gathered stones and piled them in a heap. Then Jacob and Laban sat
        down beside the pile of stones to eat a covenant meal. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "To commemorate the event, Laban called the place Jegar-sahadutha
        (which means \u201Cwitness pile\u201D in Aramaic), and Jacob called it Galeed
        (which means \u201Cwitness pile\u201D in Hebrew).  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Laban declared, \u201CThis pile of stones will stand as a witness
        to remind us of the covenant we have made today.\u201D This explains why
        it was called Galeed\u2014\u201CWitness Pile.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But it was also called Mizpah (which means \u201Cwatchtower\u201D),
        for Laban said, \u201CMay the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> keep watch between
        us to make sure that we keep this covenant when we are out of each other\u2019s
        sight. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you mistreat my daughters or if you marry other wives, God will
        see it even if no one else does. He is a witness to this covenant between
        us.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSee this pile of stones,\u201D Laban continued, \u201Cand see
        this monument I have set between us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They stand between us as witnesses of our vows. I will never pass
        this pile of stones to harm you, and you must never pass these stones or
        this monument to harm me. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I call on the God of our ancestors\u2014the God of your grandfather
        Abraham and the God of my grandfather Nahor\u2014to serve as a judge between
        us.\u201DSo Jacob took an oath before the fearsome God of his father, Isaac,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        to respect the boundary line. "
      comments:
      - number: '31:53 '
        content: 'Or <b>the Fear of his father, Isaac.</b>  '
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jacob offered a sacrifice to God there on the mountain and invited
        everyone to a covenant feast. After they had eaten, they spent the night
        on the mountain.  '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: '    [[COMMENT(0)]]As Jacob started on his way again, angels of God
        came to meet him. '
      comments:
      - number: '32:1 '
        content: '  Verses 32:1-32 are numbered 32:2-33 in Hebrew text.  '
    - title: Jacob Sends Gifts to Esau
      content: "When Jacob saw them, he exclaimed, \u201CThis is God\u2019s camp!\u201D
        So he named the place Mahanaim.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '32:2 '
        content: "<b>Mahanaim </b>means \u201Ctwo camps.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jacob sent messengers ahead to his brother, Esau, who was living
        in the region of Seir in the land of Edom. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He told them, \u201CGive this message to my master Esau: \u2018Humble
        greetings from your servant Jacob. Until now I have been living with Uncle
        Laban, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and now I own cattle, donkeys, flocks of sheep and goats, and many
        servants, both men and women. I have sent these messengers to inform my lord
        of my coming, hoping that you will be friendly to me.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After delivering the message, the messengers returned to Jacob and
        reported, \u201CWe met your brother, Esau, and he is already on his way to
        meet you\u2014with an army of 400 men!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jacob was terrified at the news. He divided his household, along
        with the flocks and herds and camels, into two groups. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He thought, \u201CIf Esau meets one group and attacks it, perhaps
        the other group can escape.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob prayed, \u201CO God of my grandfather Abraham, and God
        of my father, Isaac\u2014O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, you told me, \u2018Return
        to your own land and to your relatives.\u2019 And you promised me, \u2018I
        will treat you kindly.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I am not worthy of all the unfailing love and faithfulness you have
        shown to me, your servant. When I left home and crossed the Jordan River,
        I owned nothing except a walking stick. Now my household fills two large
        camps! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>, please rescue me from the hand of
        my brother, Esau. I am afraid that he is coming to attack me, along with
        my wives and children. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But you promised me, \u2018I will surely treat you kindly, and I
        will multiply your descendants until they become as numerous as the sands
        along the seashore\u2014too many to count.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jacob stayed where he was for the night. Then he selected these gifts
        from his possessions to present to his brother, Esau: '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '200 female goats, 20 male goats, 200 ewes, 20 rams, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: '30 female camels with their young, 40 cows, 10 bulls, 20 female donkeys,
        and 10 male donkeys. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He divided these animals into herds and assigned each to different
        servants. Then he told his servants, \u201CGo ahead of me with the animals,
        but keep some distance between the herds.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He gave these instructions to the men leading the first group: \u201CWhen
        my brother, Esau, meets you, he will ask, \u2018Whose servants are you? Where
        are you going? Who owns these animals?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You must reply, \u2018They belong to your servant Jacob, but they
        are a gift for his master Esau. Look, he is coming right behind us.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob gave the same instructions to the second and third herdsmen
        and to all who followed behind the herds: \u201CYou must say the same thing
        to Esau when you meet him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And be sure to say, \u2018Look, your servant Jacob is right behind
        us.\u2019\u201DJacob thought, \u201CI will try to appease him by sending
        gifts ahead of me. When I see him in person, perhaps he will be friendly
        to me.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: Jacob Wrestles with God
      content: 'So the gifts were sent on ahead, while Jacob himself spent that night
        in the camp.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During the night Jacob got up and took his two wives, his two servant
        wives, and his eleven sons and crossed the Jabbok River with them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'After taking them to the other side, he sent over all his possessions.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This left Jacob all alone in the camp, and a man came and wrestled
        with him until the dawn began to break. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the man saw that he would not win the match, he touched Jacob\u2019s
        hip and wrenched it out of its socket. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the man said, \u201CLet me go, for the dawn is breaking!\u201DBut
        Jacob said, \u201CI will not let you go unless you bless me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat is your name?\u201D the man asked.He replied, \u201CJacob.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYour name will no longer be Jacob,\u201D the man told him.
        \u201CFrom now on you will be called Israel,[[COMMENT(0)]] because you have
        fought with God and with men and have won.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '32:28 '
        content: "<b>Jacob </b>sounds like the Hebrew words for \u201Cheel\u201D
          and \u201Cdeceiver.\u201D <b>Israel </b>means \u201CGod fights.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlease tell me your name,\u201D Jacob said.\u201CWhy do you
        want to know my name?\u201D the man replied. Then he blessed Jacob there.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob named the place Peniel (which means \u201Cface of God\u201D),
        for he said, \u201CI have seen God face to face, yet my life has been spared.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sun was rising as Jacob left Peniel,[[COMMENT(0)]] and he was
        limping because of the injury to his hip. '
      comments:
      - number: '32:31 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Penuel, </b>a variant spelling of Peniel.
  - verses:
    - title: Jacob and Esau Make Peace
      content: '  Then Jacob looked up and saw Esau coming with his 400 men. So he
        divided the children among Leah, Rachel, and his two servant wives. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He put the servant wives and their children at the front, Leah and
        her children next, and Rachel and Joseph last. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jacob went on ahead. As he approached his brother, he bowed
        to the ground seven times before him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Esau ran to meet him and embraced him, threw his arms around
        his neck, and kissed him. And they both wept.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Esau looked at the women and children and asked, \u201CWho are
        these people with you?\u201D\u201CThese are the children God has graciously
        given to me, your servant,\u201D Jacob replied. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the servant wives came forward with their children and bowed
        before him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Next came Leah with her children, and they bowed before him. Finally,
        Joseph and Rachel came forward and bowed before him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd what were all the flocks and herds I met as I came?\u201D
        Esau asked.Jacob replied, \u201CThey are a gift, my lord, to ensure your
        friendship.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMy brother, I have plenty,\u201D Esau answered. \u201CKeep
        what you have for yourself.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Jacob insisted, \u201CNo, if I have found favor with you, please
        accept this gift from me. And what a relief to see your friendly smile. It
        is like seeing the face of God! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Please take this gift I have brought you, for God has been very gracious
        to me. I have more than enough.\u201D And because Jacob insisted, Esau finally
        accepted the gift.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWell,\u201D Esau said, \u201Clet\u2019s be going. I will lead
        the way.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Jacob replied, \u201CYou can see, my lord, that some of the children
        are very young, and the flocks and herds have their young, too. If they are
        driven too hard, even for one day, all the animals could die. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Please, my lord, go ahead of your servant. We will follow slowly,
        at a pace that is comfortable for the livestock and the children. I will
        meet you at Seir.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAll right,\u201D Esau said, \u201Cbut at least let me assign
        some of my men to guide and protect you.\u201DJacob responded, \u201CThat\u2019s
        not necessary. It\u2019s enough that you\u2019ve received me warmly, my lord!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Esau turned around and started back to Seir that same day. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob, on the other hand, traveled on to Succoth. There he built
        himself a house and made shelters for his livestock. That is why the place
        was named Succoth (which means \u201Cshelters\u201D).  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Later, having traveled all the way from Paddan-aram, Jacob arrived
        safely at the town of Shechem, in the land of Canaan. There he set up camp
        outside the town. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jacob bought the plot of land where he camped from the family of
        Hamor, the father of Shechem, for 100 pieces of silver.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '33:19 '
        content: Hebrew <b>100 kesitahs; </b>the value or weight of the kesitah is
          no longer known.
  - verses:
    - title: Revenge against Shechem
      content: '  One day Dinah, the daughter of Jacob and Leah, went to visit some
        of the young women who lived in the area. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when the local prince, Shechem son of Hamor the Hivite, saw Dinah,
        he seized her and raped her. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But then he fell in love with her, and he tried to win her affection
        with tender words. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He said to his father, Hamor, \u201CGet me this young girl. I want
        to marry her.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Soon Jacob heard that Shechem had defiled his daughter, Dinah. But
        since his sons were out in the fields herding his livestock, he said nothing
        until they returned. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Hamor, Shechem\u2019s father, came to discuss the matter with Jacob. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, Jacob\u2019s sons had come in from the field as soon as
        they heard what had happened. They were shocked and furious that their sister
        had been raped. Shechem had done a disgraceful thing against Jacob\u2019s
        family,[[COMMENT(0)]] something that should never be done.  "
      comments:
      - number: '34:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a disgraceful thing in Israel.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Hamor tried to speak with Jacob and his sons. \u201CMy son Shechem
        is truly in love with your daughter,\u201D he said. \u201CPlease let him
        marry her. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "In fact, let\u2019s arrange other marriages, too. You give us your
        daughters for our sons, and we will give you our daughters for your sons. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And you may live among us; the land is open to you! Settle here and
        trade with us. And feel free to buy property in the area.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Shechem himself spoke to Dinah\u2019s father and brothers. \u201CPlease
        be kind to me, and let me marry her,\u201D he begged. \u201CI will give you
        whatever you ask. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No matter what dowry or gift you demand, I will gladly pay it\u2014just
        give me the girl as my wife.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But since Shechem had defiled their sister, Dinah, Jacob\u2019s sons
        responded deceitfully to Shechem and his father, Hamor. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They said to them, \u201CWe couldn\u2019t possibly allow this, because
        you\u2019re not circumcised. It would be a disgrace for our sister to marry
        a man like you! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But here is a solution. If every man among you will be circumcised
        like we are, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "then we will give you our daughters, and we\u2019ll take your daughters
        for ourselves. We will live among you and become one people. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if you don\u2019t agree to be circumcised, we will take her and
        be on our way.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Hamor and his son Shechem agreed to their proposal. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Shechem wasted no time in acting on this request, for he wanted Jacob\u2019s
        daughter desperately. Shechem was a highly respected member of his family, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he went with his father, Hamor, to present this proposal to the
        leaders at the town gate.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThese men are our friends,\u201D they said. \u201CLet\u2019s
        invite them to live here among us and trade freely. Look, the land is large
        enough to hold them. We can take their daughters as wives and let them marry
        ours. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But they will consider staying here and becoming one people with
        us only if all of our men are circumcised, just as they are. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if we do this, all their livestock and possessions will eventually
        be ours. Come, let\u2019s agree to their terms and let them settle here among
        us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So all the men in the town council agreed with Hamor and Shechem,
        and every male in the town was circumcised. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But three days later, when their wounds were still sore, two of Jacob\u2019s
        sons, Simeon and Levi, who were Dinah\u2019s full brothers, took their swords
        and entered the town without opposition. Then they slaughtered every male
        there, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "including Hamor and his son Shechem. They killed them with their
        swords, then took Dinah from Shechem\u2019s house and returned to their camp.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Meanwhile, the rest of Jacob\u2019s sons arrived. Finding the men
        slaughtered, they plundered the town because their sister had been defiled
        there. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They seized all the flocks and herds and donkeys\u2014everything
        they could lay their hands on, both inside the town and outside in the fields. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They looted all their wealth and plundered their houses. They also
        took all their little children and wives and led them away as captives.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Afterward Jacob said to Simeon and Levi, \u201CYou have ruined me!
        You\u2019ve made me stink among all the people of this land\u2014among all
        the Canaanites and Perizzites. We are so few that they will join forces and
        crush us. I will be ruined, and my entire household will be wiped out!\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Return to Bethel"
      content: "  Then God said to Jacob, \u201CGet ready and move to Bethel and
        settle there. Build an altar there to the God who appeared to you when you
        fled from your brother, Esau.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jacob told everyone in his household, \u201CGet rid of all your
        pagan idols, purify yourselves, and put on clean clothing. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We are now going to Bethel, where I will build an altar to the God
        who answered my prayers when I was in distress. He has been with me wherever
        I have gone.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they gave Jacob all their pagan idols and earrings, and he buried
        them under the great tree near Shechem. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As they set out, a terror from God spread over the people in all
        the towns of that area, so no one attacked Jacob\u2019s family.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Eventually, Jacob and his household arrived at Luz (also called Bethel)
        in Canaan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob built an altar there and named the place El-bethel (which means
        \u201CGod of Bethel\u201D), because God had appeared to him there when he
        was fleeing from his brother, Esau.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Soon after this, Rebekah\u2019s old nurse, Deborah, died. She was
        buried beneath the oak tree in the valley below Bethel. Ever since, the tree
        has been called Allon-bacuth (which means \u201Coak of weeping\u201D).  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now that Jacob had returned from Paddan-aram, God appeared to him
        again at Bethel. God blessed him, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "saying, \u201CYour name is Jacob, but you will not be called Jacob
        any longer. From now on your name will be Israel.\u201D[[COMMENT(0)]] So
        God renamed him Israel.  "
      comments:
      - number: '35:10 '
        content: "<b>Jacob </b>sounds like the Hebrew words for \u201Cheel\u201D
          and \u201Cdeceiver.\u201D <b>Israel </b>means \u201CGod fights.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "Then God said, \u201CI am El-Shaddai\u2014\u2018God Almighty.\u2019
        Be fruitful and multiply. You will become a great nation, even many nations.
        Kings will be among your descendants! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And I will give you the land I once gave to Abraham and Isaac. Yes,
        I will give it to you and your descendants after you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then God went up from the place where he had spoken to Jacob.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jacob set up a stone pillar to mark the place where God had spoken
        to him. Then he poured wine over it as an offering to God and anointed the
        pillar with olive oil. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Deaths of Rachel and Isaac
      content: "And Jacob named the place Bethel (which means \u201Chouse of God\u201D),
        because God had spoken to him there.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Leaving Bethel, Jacob and his clan moved on toward Ephrath. But Rachel
        went into labor while they were still some distance away. Her labor pains
        were intense. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After a very hard delivery, the midwife finally exclaimed, \u201CDon\u2019t
        be afraid\u2014you have another son!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Rachel was about to die, but with her last breath she named the baby
        Ben-oni (which means \u201Cson of my sorrow\u201D). The baby\u2019s father,
        however, called him Benjamin (which means \u201Cson of my right hand\u201D). "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Rachel died and was buried on the way to Ephrath (that is, Bethlehem). '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob set up a stone monument over Rachel\u2019s grave, and it can
        be seen there to this day.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jacob[[COMMENT(0)]] traveled on and camped beyond Migdal-eder. '
      comments:
      - number: '35:21 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>Israel; </b>also in 35:22a. The names \u201CJacob\u201D
          and \u201CIsrael\u201D are often interchanged throughout the Old Testament,
          referring sometimes to the individual patriarch and sometimes to the nation."
    - title: 
      content: "While he was living there, Reuben had intercourse with Bilhah, his
        father\u2019s concubine, and Jacob soon heard about it.These are the names
        of the twelve sons of Jacob:  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The sons of Leah were Reuben (Jacob\u2019s oldest son), Simeon, Levi,
        Judah, Issachar, and Zebulun.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Rachel were Joseph and Benjamin.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The sons of Bilhah, Rachel\u2019s servant, were Dan and Naphtali.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The sons of Zilpah, Leah\u2019s servant, were Gad and Asher.These
        are the names of the sons who were born to Jacob at Paddan-aram.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob returned to his father, Isaac, in Mamre, which is near Kiriath-arba
        (now called Hebron), where Abraham and Isaac had both lived as foreigners. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Isaac lived for 180 years. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Descendants of Esau
      content: '  This is the account of the descendants of Esau (also known as Edom). '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Esau married two young women from Canaan: Adah, the daughter of Elon
        the Hittite; and Oholibamah, the daughter of Anah and granddaughter of Zibeon
        the Hivite. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He also married his cousin Basemath, who was the daughter of Ishmael
        and the sister of Nebaioth. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Adah gave birth to a son named Eliphaz for Esau. Basemath gave birth
        to a son named Reuel. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Oholibamah gave birth to sons named Jeush, Jalam, and Korah. All
        these sons were born to Esau in the land of Canaan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Esau took his wives, his children, and his entire household, along
        with his livestock and cattle\u2014all the wealth he had acquired in the
        land of Canaan\u2014and moved away from his brother, Jacob. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There was not enough land to support them both because of all the
        livestock and possessions they had acquired. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Esau (also known as Edom) settled in the hill country of Seir.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is the account of Esau\u2019s descendants, the Edomites, who
        lived in the hill country of Seir.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These are the names of Esau\u2019s sons: Eliphaz, the son of Esau\u2019s
        wife Adah; and Reuel, the son of Esau\u2019s wife Basemath.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Eliphaz were Teman, Omar, Zepho, Gatam, and Kenaz. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Timna, the concubine of Esau\u2019s son Eliphaz, gave birth to a
        son named Amalek. These are the descendants of Esau\u2019s wife Adah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Reuel were Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah.
        These are the descendants of Esau\u2019s wife Basemath.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Esau also had sons through Oholibamah, the daughter of Anah and granddaughter
        of Zibeon. Their names were Jeush, Jalam, and Korah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These are the descendants of Esau who became the leaders of various
        clans:The descendants of Esau\u2019s oldest son, Eliphaz, became the leaders
        of the clans of Teman, Omar, Zepho, Kenaz, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Korah, Gatam, and Amalek. These are the clan leaders in the land
        of Edom who descended from Eliphaz. All these were descendants of Esau\u2019s
        wife Adah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Esau\u2019s son Reuel became the leaders of the
        clans of Nahath, Zerah, Shammah, and Mizzah. These are the clan leaders in
        the land of Edom who descended from Reuel. All these were descendants of
        Esau\u2019s wife Basemath.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Esau and his wife Oholibamah became the leaders
        of the clans of Jeush, Jalam, and Korah. These are the clan leaders who descended
        from Esau\u2019s wife Oholibamah, the daughter of Anah.  "
      comments: []
    - title: Original Peoples of Edom
      content: 'These are the clans descended from Esau (also known as Edom), identified
        by their clan leaders.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These are the names of the tribes that descended from Seir the Horite.
        They lived in the land of Edom: Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon, Anah, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan. These were the Horite clan leaders, the
        descendants of Seir, who lived in the land of Edom.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Lotan were Hori and Hemam. Lotan\u2019s sister
        was named Timna.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Shobal were Alvan, Manahath, Ebal, Shepho, and
        Onam.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The descendants of Zibeon were Aiah and Anah. (This is the Anah who
        discovered the hot springs in the wilderness while he was grazing his father\u2019s
        donkeys.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Anah were his son, Dishon, and his daughter, Oholibamah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Dishon[[COMMENT(0)]] were Hemdan, Eshban, Ithran,
        and Keran.  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Dishan, </b>a variant spelling of Dishon; compare 36:21,
          28.
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Ezer were Bilhan, Zaavan, and Akan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The descendants of Dishan were Uz and Aran.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So these were the leaders of the Horite clans: Lotan, Shobal, Zibeon,
        Anah, '
      comments: []
    - title: Rulers of Edom
      content: 'Dishon, Ezer, and Dishan. The Horite clans are named after their
        clan leaders, who lived in the land of Seir.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These are the kings who ruled in the land of Edom before any king
        ruled over the Israelites[[COMMENT(0)]]:  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:31 '
        content: Or <b>before an Israelite king ruled over them.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'Bela son of Beor, who ruled in Edom from his city of Dinhabah.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Bela died, Jobab son of Zerah from Bozrah became king in his
        place.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Jobab died, Husham from the land of the Temanites became king
        in his place.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Husham died, Hadad son of Bedad became king in his place and
        ruled from the city of Avith. He was the one who defeated the Midianites
        in the land of Moab.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Hadad died, Samlah from the city of Masrekah became king in
        his place.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Samlah died, Shaul from the city of Rehoboth-on-the-River became
        king in his place.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Shaul died, Baal-hanan son of Acbor became king in his place.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Baal-hanan son of Acbor died, Hadad[[COMMENT(0)]] became king
        in his place and ruled from the city of Pau. His wife was Mehetabel, the
        daughter of Matred and granddaughter of Me-zahab.  '
      comments:
      - number: '36:39 '
        content: As in some Hebrew manuscripts, Samaritan Pentateuch, and Syriac
          version (see also 1 Chr 1:50); most Hebrew manuscripts read <b>Hadar.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'These are the names of the leaders of the clans descended from Esau,
        who lived in the places named for them: Timna, Alvah, Jetheth, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Oholibamah, Elah, Pinon, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Kenaz, Teman, Mibzar, '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Joseph\u2019s Dreams"
      content: '  So Jacob settled again in the land of Canaan, where his father
        had lived as a foreigner.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This is the account of Jacob and his family. When Joseph was seventeen
        years old, he often tended his father\u2019s flocks. He worked for his half
        brothers, the sons of his father\u2019s wives Bilhah and Zilpah. But Joseph
        reported to his father some of the bad things his brothers were doing.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob[[COMMENT(0)]] loved Joseph more than any of his other children
        because Joseph had been born to him in his old age. So one day Jacob had
        a special gift made for Joseph\u2014a beautiful robe.[[COMMENT(1)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '37:3a '
        content: Hebrew <b>Israel; </b>also in 37:13. See note on 35:21.
      - number: '37:3b '
        content: Traditionally rendered <b>a coat of many colors. </b>The exact meaning
          of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "But his brothers hated Joseph because their father loved him more
        than the rest of them. They couldn\u2019t say a kind word to him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One night Joseph had a dream, and when he told his brothers about
        it, they hated him more than ever. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CListen to this dream,\u201D he said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWe were out in the field, tying up bundles of grain. Suddenly
        my bundle stood up, and your bundles all gathered around and bowed low before
        mine!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "His brothers responded, \u201CSo you think you will be our king,
        do you? Do you actually think you will reign over us?\u201D And they hated
        him all the more because of his dreams and the way he talked about them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Soon Joseph had another dream, and again he told his brothers about
        it. \u201CListen, I have had another dream,\u201D he said. \u201CThe sun,
        moon, and eleven stars bowed low before me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "This time he told the dream to his father as well as to his brothers,
        but his father scolded him. \u201CWhat kind of dream is that?\u201D he asked.
        \u201CWill your mother and I and your brothers actually come and bow to the
        ground before you?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But while his brothers were jealous of Joseph, his father wondered
        what the dreams meant.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Soon after this, Joseph\u2019s brothers went to pasture their father\u2019s
        flocks at Shechem. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they had been gone for some time, Jacob said to Joseph, \u201CYour
        brothers are pasturing the sheep at Shechem. Get ready, and I will send you
        to them.\u201D\u201CI\u2019m ready to go,\u201D Joseph replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGo and see how your brothers and the flocks are getting along,\u201D
        Jacob said. \u201CThen come back and bring me a report.\u201D So Jacob sent
        him on his way, and Joseph traveled to Shechem from their home in the valley
        of Hebron.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When he arrived there, a man from the area noticed him wandering
        around the countryside. \u201CWhat are you looking for?\u201D he asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI\u2019m looking for my brothers,\u201D Joseph replied. \u201CDo
        you know where they are pasturing their sheep?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Joseph Sold into Slavery
      content: "\u201CYes,\u201D the man told him. \u201CThey have moved on from
        here, but I heard them say, \u2018Let\u2019s go on to Dothan.\u2019\u201D
        So Joseph followed his brothers to Dothan and found them there.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Joseph\u2019s brothers saw him coming, they recognized him in
        the distance. As he approached, they made plans to kill him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHere comes the dreamer!\u201D they said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCome on, let\u2019s kill him and throw him into one of these
        cisterns. We can tell our father, \u2018A wild animal has eaten him.\u2019
        Then we\u2019ll see what becomes of his dreams!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when Reuben heard of their scheme, he came to Joseph\u2019s rescue.
        \u201CLet\u2019s not kill him,\u201D he said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy should we shed any blood? Let\u2019s just throw him into
        this empty cistern here in the wilderness. Then he\u2019ll die without our
        laying a hand on him.\u201D Reuben was secretly planning to rescue Joseph
        and return him to his father.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So when Joseph arrived, his brothers ripped off the beautiful robe
        he was wearing. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then they grabbed him and threw him into the cistern. Now the cistern
        was empty; there was no water in it. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then, just as they were sitting down to eat, they looked up and saw
        a caravan of camels in the distance coming toward them. It was a group of
        Ishmaelite traders taking a load of gum, balm, and aromatic resin from Gilead
        down to Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Judah said to his brothers, \u201CWhat will we gain by killing our
        brother? We\u2019d have to cover up the crime.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '37:26 '
        content: Hebrew <b>cover his blood.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Instead of hurting him, let\u2019s sell him to those Ishmaelite traders.
        After all, he is our brother\u2014our own flesh and blood!\u201D And his
        brothers agreed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So when the Ishmaelites, who were Midianite traders, came by, Joseph\u2019s
        brothers pulled him out of the cistern and sold him to them for twenty pieces[[COMMENT(0)]]
        of silver. And the traders took him to Egypt.  "
      comments:
      - number: '37:28 '
        content: Hebrew <b>20 [shekels], </b>about 8 ounces or 228 grams in weight.
    - title: 
      content: 'Some time later, Reuben returned to get Joseph out of the cistern.
        When he discovered that Joseph was missing, he tore his clothes in grief. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he went back to his brothers and lamented, \u201CThe boy is
        gone! What will I do now?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then the brothers killed a young goat and dipped Joseph\u2019s robe
        in its blood. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They sent the beautiful robe to their father with this message: \u201CLook
        at what we found. Doesn\u2019t this robe belong to your son?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Their father recognized it immediately. \u201CYes,\u201D he said,
        \u201Cit is my son\u2019s robe. A wild animal must have eaten him. Joseph
        has clearly been torn to pieces!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jacob tore his clothes and dressed himself in burlap. He mourned
        deeply for his son for a long time. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "His family all tried to comfort him, but he refused to be comforted.
        \u201CI will go to my grave[[COMMENT(0)]] mourning for my son,\u201D he would
        say, and then he would weep.  "
      comments:
      - number: '37:35 '
        content: Hebrew <b>go down to Sheol.</b>
  - verses:
    - title: Judah and Tamar
      content: '  About this time, Judah left home and moved to Adullam, where he
        stayed with a man named Hirah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There he saw a Canaanite woman, the daughter of Shua, and he married
        her. When he slept with her, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'she became pregnant and gave birth to a son, and he named the boy
        Er. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then she became pregnant again and gave birth to another son, and
        she named him Onan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And when she gave birth to a third son, she named him Shelah. At
        the time of Shelah\u2019s birth, they were living at Kezib.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In the course of time, Judah arranged for his firstborn son, Er,
        to marry a young woman named Tamar. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Er was a wicked man in the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>\u2019s
        sight, so the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> took his life. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Judah said to Er\u2019s brother Onan, \u201CGo and marry Tamar,
        as our law requires of the brother of a man who has died. You must produce
        an heir for your brother.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Onan was not willing to have a child who would not be his own
        heir. So whenever he had intercourse with his brother\u2019s wife, he spilled
        the semen on the ground. This prevented her from having a child who would
        belong to his brother. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> considered it evil for Onan to
        deny a child to his dead brother. So the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> took
        Onan\u2019s life, too.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Judah said to Tamar, his daughter-in-law, \u201CGo back to your
        parents\u2019 home and remain a widow until my son Shelah is old enough to
        marry you.\u201D (But Judah didn\u2019t really intend to do this because
        he was afraid Shelah would also die, like his two brothers.) So Tamar went
        back to live in her father\u2019s home.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Some years later Judah\u2019s wife died. After the time of mourning
        was over, Judah and his friend Hirah the Adullamite went up to Timnah to
        supervise the shearing of his sheep. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Someone told Tamar, \u201CLook, your father-in-law is going up to
        Timnah to shear his sheep.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Tamar was aware that Shelah had grown up, but no arrangements had
        been made for her to come and marry him. So she changed out of her widow\u2019s
        clothing and covered herself with a veil to disguise herself. Then she sat
        beside the road at the entrance to the village of Enaim, which is on the
        road to Timnah. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Judah noticed her and thought she was a prostitute, since she had
        covered her face. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So he stopped and propositioned her. \u201CLet me have sex with you,\u201D
        he said, not realizing that she was his own daughter-in-law.\u201CHow much
        will you pay to have sex with me?\u201D Tamar asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI\u2019ll send you a young goat from my flock,\u201D Judah
        promised.\u201CBut what will you give me to guarantee that you will send
        the goat?\u201D she asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat kind of guarantee do you want?\u201D he replied.She answered,
        \u201CLeave me your identification seal and its cord and the walking stick
        you are carrying.\u201D So Judah gave them to her. Then he had intercourse
        with her, and she became pregnant. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Afterward she went back home, took off her veil, and put on her widow\u2019s
        clothing as usual.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Later Judah asked his friend Hirah the Adullamite to take the young
        goat to the woman and to pick up the things he had given her as his guarantee.
        But Hirah couldn\u2019t find her. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So he asked the men who lived there, \u201CWhere can I find the shrine
        prostitute who was sitting beside the road at the entrance to Enaim?\u201D\u201CWe\u2019ve
        never had a shrine prostitute here,\u201D they replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Hirah returned to Judah and told him, \u201CI couldn\u2019t find
        her anywhere, and the men of the village claim they\u2019ve never had a shrine
        prostitute there.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen let her keep the things I gave her,\u201D Judah said.
        \u201CI sent the young goat as we agreed, but you couldn\u2019t find her.
        We\u2019d be the laughingstock of the village if we went back again to look
        for her.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "About three months later, Judah was told, \u201CTamar, your daughter-in-law,
        has acted like a prostitute. And now, because of this, she\u2019s pregnant.\u201D\u201CBring
        her out, and let her be burned!\u201D Judah demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But as they were taking her out to kill her, she sent this message
        to her father-in-law: \u201CThe man who owns these things made me pregnant.
        Look closely. Whose seal and cord and walking stick are these?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Judah recognized them immediately and said, \u201CShe is more righteous
        than I am, because I didn\u2019t arrange for her to marry my son Shelah.\u201D
        And Judah never slept with Tamar again.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the time came for Tamar to give birth, it was discovered that
        she was carrying twins. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "While she was in labor, one of the babies reached out his hand. The
        midwife grabbed it and tied a scarlet string around the child\u2019s wrist,
        announcing, \u201CThis one came out first.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But then he pulled back his hand, and out came his brother! \u201CWhat!\u201D
        the midwife exclaimed. \u201CHow did you break out first?\u201D So he was
        named Perez.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '38:29 '
        content: "<b>Perez </b>means \u201Cbreaking out.\u201D"
  - verses:
    - title: "Joseph in Potiphar\u2019s House"
      content: '  When Joseph was taken to Egypt by the Ishmaelite traders, he was
        purchased by Potiphar, an Egyptian officer. Potiphar was captain of the guard
        for Pharaoh, the king of Egypt.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was with Joseph, so he succeeded
        in everything he did as he served in the home of his Egyptian master. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Potiphar noticed this and realized that the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>
        was with Joseph, giving him success in everything he did. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This pleased Potiphar, so he soon made Joseph his personal attendant.
        He put him in charge of his entire household and everything he owned. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "From the day Joseph was put in charge of his master\u2019s household
        and property, the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> began to bless Potiphar\u2019s
        household for Joseph\u2019s sake. All his household affairs ran smoothly,
        and his crops and livestock flourished. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Potiphar gave Joseph complete administrative responsibility over
        everything he owned. With Joseph there, he didn\u2019t worry about a thing\u2014except
        what kind of food to eat!Joseph was a very handsome and well-built young
        man, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "and Potiphar\u2019s wife soon began to look at him lustfully. \u201CCome
        and sleep with me,\u201D she demanded.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Joseph refused. \u201CLook,\u201D he told her, \u201Cmy master
        trusts me with everything in his entire household. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "No one here has more authority than I do. He has held back nothing
        from me except you, because you are his wife. How could I do such a wicked
        thing? It would be a great sin against God.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'She kept putting pressure on Joseph day after day, but he refused
        to sleep with her, and he kept out of her way as much as possible. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One day, however, no one else was around when he went in to do his
        work. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "She came and grabbed him by his cloak, demanding, \u201CCome on,
        sleep with me!\u201D Joseph tore himself away, but he left his cloak in her
        hand as he ran from the house.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When she saw that she was holding his cloak and he had fled, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "she called out to her servants. Soon all the men came running. \u201CLook!\u201D
        she said. \u201CMy husband has brought this Hebrew slave here to make fools
        of us! He came into my room to rape me, but I screamed. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When he heard me scream, he ran outside and got away, but he left
        his cloak behind with me.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'She kept the cloak with her until her husband came home. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then she told him her story. \u201CThat Hebrew slave you\u2019ve
        brought into our house tried to come in and fool around with me,\u201D she
        said. "
      comments: []
    - title: Joseph Put in Prison
      content: "\u201CBut when I screamed, he ran outside, leaving his cloak with
        me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Potiphar was furious when he heard his wife\u2019s story about how
        Joseph had treated her. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So he took Joseph and threw him into the prison where the king\u2019s
        prisoners were held, and there he remained. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> was with Joseph in the prison
        and showed him his faithful love. And the <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps> made
        Joseph a favorite with the prison warden. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Before long, the warden put Joseph in charge of all the other prisoners
        and over everything that happened in the prison. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Joseph Interprets Two Dreams
      content: "  Some time later, Pharaoh\u2019s chief cup-bearer and chief baker
        offended their royal master. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pharaoh became angry with these two officials, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and he put them in the prison where Joseph was, in the palace of
        the captain of the guard. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They remained in prison for quite some time, and the captain of the
        guard assigned them to Joseph, who looked after them.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "While they were in prison, Pharaoh\u2019s cup-bearer and baker each
        had a dream one night, and each dream had its own meaning. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Joseph saw them the next morning, he noticed that they both
        looked upset. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy do you look so worried today?\u201D he asked them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And they replied, \u201CWe both had dreams last night, but no one
        can tell us what they mean.\u201D\u201CInterpreting dreams is God\u2019s
        business,\u201D Joseph replied. \u201CGo ahead and tell me your dreams.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the chief cup-bearer told Joseph his dream first. \u201CIn my
        dream,\u201D he said, \u201CI saw a grapevine in front of me. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The vine had three branches that began to bud and blossom, and soon
        it produced clusters of ripe grapes. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I was holding Pharaoh\u2019s wine cup in my hand, so I took a cluster
        of grapes and squeezed the juice into the cup. Then I placed the cup in Pharaoh\u2019s
        hand.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the dream means,\u201D Joseph said. \u201CThe
        three branches represent three days. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Within three days Pharaoh will lift you up and restore you to your
        position as his chief cup-bearer. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And please remember me and do me a favor when things go well for
        you. Mention me to Pharaoh, so he might let me out of this place. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "For I was kidnapped from my homeland, the land of the Hebrews, and
        now I\u2019m here in prison, but I did nothing to deserve it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the chief baker saw that Joseph had given the first dream such
        a positive interpretation, he said to Joseph, \u201CI had a dream, too. In
        my dream there were three baskets of white pastries stacked on my head. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The top basket contained all kinds of pastries for Pharaoh, but the
        birds came and ate them from the basket on my head.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis is what the dream means,\u201D Joseph told him. \u201CThe
        three baskets also represent three days. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Three days from now Pharaoh will lift you up and impale your body
        on a pole. Then birds will come and peck away at your flesh.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh\u2019s birthday came three days later, and he prepared a
        banquet for all his officials and staff. He summoned[[COMMENT(0)]] his chief
        cup-bearer and chief baker to join the other officials. "
      comments:
      - number: '40:20 '
        content: Hebrew <b>He lifted up the head of.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He then restored the chief cup-bearer to his former position, so
        he could again hand Pharaoh his cup. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But Pharaoh impaled the chief baker, just as Joseph had predicted
        when he interpreted his dream. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Pharaoh\u2019s Dreams"
      content: '  Two full years later, Pharaoh dreamed that he was standing on the
        bank of the Nile River. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'In his dream he saw seven fat, healthy cows come up out of the river
        and begin grazing in the marsh grass. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then he saw seven more cows come up behind them from the Nile, but
        these were scrawny and thin. These cows stood beside the fat cows on the
        riverbank. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the scrawny, thin cows ate the seven healthy, fat cows! At this
        point in the dream, Pharaoh woke up.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But he fell asleep again and had a second dream. This time he saw
        seven heads of grain, plump and beautiful, growing on a single stalk. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then seven more heads of grain appeared, but these were shriveled
        and withered by the east wind. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And these thin heads swallowed up the seven plump, well-formed heads!
        Then Pharaoh woke up again and realized it was a dream.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next morning Pharaoh was very disturbed by the dreams. So he
        called for all the magicians and wise men of Egypt. When Pharaoh told them
        his dreams, not one of them could tell him what they meant.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, the king\u2019s chief cup-bearer spoke up. \u201CToday I
        have been reminded of my failure,\u201D he told Pharaoh. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSome time ago, you were angry with the chief baker and me,
        and you imprisoned us in the palace of the captain of the guard. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'One night the chief baker and I each had a dream, and each dream
        had its own meaning. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There was a young Hebrew man with us in the prison who was a slave
        of the captain of the guard. We told him our dreams, and he told us what
        each of our dreams meant. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And everything happened just as he had predicted. I was restored
        to my position as cup-bearer, and the chief baker was executed and impaled
        on a pole.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Pharaoh sent for Joseph at once, and he was quickly brought from
        the prison. After he shaved and changed his clothes, he went in and stood
        before Pharaoh. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CI had a dream last night, and
        no one here can tell me what it means. But I have heard that when you hear
        about a dream you can interpret it.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIt is beyond my power to do this,\u201D Joseph replied. \u201CBut
        God can tell you what it means and set you at ease.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Pharaoh told Joseph his dream. \u201CIn my dream,\u201D he said,
        \u201CI was standing on the bank of the Nile River, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and I saw seven fat, healthy cows come up out of the river and begin
        grazing in the marsh grass. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But then I saw seven sick-looking cows, scrawny and thin, come up
        after them. I\u2019ve never seen such sorry-looking animals in all the land
        of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'These thin, scrawny cows ate the seven fat cows. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But afterward you wouldn\u2019t have known it, for they were still
        as thin and scrawny as before! Then I woke up.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIn my dream I also saw seven heads of grain, full and beautiful,
        growing on a single stalk. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then seven more heads of grain appeared, but these were blighted,
        shriveled, and withered by the east wind. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And the shriveled heads swallowed the seven healthy heads. I told
        these dreams to the magicians, but no one could tell me what they mean.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph responded, \u201CBoth of Pharaoh\u2019s dreams mean the same
        thing. God is telling Pharaoh in advance what he is about to do. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The seven healthy cows and the seven healthy heads of grain both
        represent seven years of prosperity. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The seven thin, scrawny cows that came up later and the seven thin
        heads of grain, withered by the east wind, represent seven years of famine.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThis will happen just as I have described it, for God has revealed
        to Pharaoh in advance what he is about to do. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The next seven years will be a period of great prosperity throughout
        the land of Egypt. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But afterward there will be seven years of famine so great that all
        the prosperity will be forgotten in Egypt. Famine will destroy the land. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This famine will be so severe that even the memory of the good years
        will be erased. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As for having two similar dreams, it means that these events have
        been decreed by God, and he will soon make them happen.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CTherefore, Pharaoh should find an intelligent and wise man
        and put him in charge of the entire land of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Pharaoh should appoint supervisors over the land and let them
        collect one-fifth of all the crops during the seven good years. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Have them gather all the food produced in the good years that are
        just ahead and bring it to Pharaoh\u2019s storehouses. Store it away, and
        guard it so there will be food in the cities. "
      comments: []
    - title: Joseph Made Ruler of Egypt
      content: "That way there will be enough to eat when the seven years of famine
        come to the land of Egypt. Otherwise this famine will destroy the land.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph\u2019s suggestions were well received by Pharaoh and his officials. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Pharaoh asked his officials, \u201CCan we find anyone else like
        this man so obviously filled with the spirit of God?\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CSince God has revealed the meaning
        of the dreams to you, clearly no one else is as intelligent or wise as you
        are. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "You will be in charge of my court, and all my people will take orders
        from you. Only I, sitting on my throne, will have a rank higher than yours.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CI hereby put you in charge of the entire
        land of Egypt.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh removed his signet ring from his hand and placed it
        on Joseph\u2019s finger. He dressed him in fine linen clothing and hung a
        gold chain around his neck. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he had Joseph ride in the chariot reserved for his second-in-command.
        And wherever Joseph went, the command was shouted, \u201CKneel down!\u201D
        So Pharaoh put Joseph in charge of all Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Pharaoh said to him, \u201CI am Pharaoh, but no one will lift
        a hand or foot in the entire land of Egypt without your approval.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Pharaoh gave Joseph a new Egyptian name, Zaphenath-paneah.[[COMMENT(0)]]
        He also gave him a wife, whose name was Asenath. She was the daughter of
        Potiphera, the priest of On.[[COMMENT(1)]] So Joseph took charge of the entire
        land of Egypt. '
      comments:
      - number: '41:45a '
        content: "<b>Zaphenath-paneah </b>probably means \u201CGod speaks and lives.\u201D"
      - number: '41:45b '
        content: Greek version reads <b>of Heliopolis; </b>also in 41:50.
    - title: 
      content: "He was thirty years old when he began serving in the court of Pharaoh,
        the king of Egypt. And when Joseph left Pharaoh\u2019s presence, he inspected
        the entire land of Egypt.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As predicted, for seven years the land produced bumper crops. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During those years, Joseph gathered all the crops grown in Egypt
        and stored the grain from the surrounding fields in the cities. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'He piled up huge amounts of grain like sand on the seashore. Finally,
        he stopped keeping records because there was too much to measure.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'During this time, before the first of the famine years, two sons
        were born to Joseph and his wife, Asenath, the daughter of Potiphera, the
        priest of On. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph named his older son Manasseh,[[COMMENT(0)]] for he said, \u201CGod
        has made me forget all my troubles and everyone in my father\u2019s family.\u201D "
      comments:
      - number: '41:51 '
        content: "<b>Manasseh </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Ccausing
          to forget.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph named his second son Ephraim,[[COMMENT(0)]] for he said, \u201CGod
        has made me fruitful in this land of my grief.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '41:52 '
        content: "<b>Ephraim </b>sounds like a Hebrew term that means \u201Cfruitful.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: 'At last the seven years of bumper crops throughout the land of Egypt
        came to an end. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then the seven years of famine began, just as Joseph had predicted.
        The famine also struck all the surrounding countries, but throughout Egypt
        there was plenty of food. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Eventually, however, the famine spread throughout the land of Egypt
        as well. And when the people cried out to Pharaoh for food, he told them,
        \u201CGo to Joseph, and do whatever he tells you.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So with severe famine everywhere, Joseph opened up the storehouses
        and distributed grain to the Egyptians, for the famine was severe throughout
        the land of Egypt. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Joseph\u2019s Brothers Go to Egypt"
      content: "  When Jacob heard that grain was available in Egypt, he said to
        his sons, \u201CWhy are you standing around looking at one another? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I have heard there is grain in Egypt. Go down there, and buy enough
        grain to keep us alive. Otherwise we\u2019ll die.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joseph\u2019s ten older brothers went down to Egypt to buy grain. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Jacob wouldn\u2019t let Joseph\u2019s younger brother, Benjamin,
        go with them, for fear some harm might come to him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jacob\u2019s[[COMMENT(0)]] sons arrived in Egypt along with others
        to buy food, for the famine was in Canaan as well.  "
      comments:
      - number: '42:5 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>Israel\u2019s. </b>See note on 35:21."
    - title: 
      content: 'Since Joseph was governor of all Egypt and in charge of selling grain
        to all the people, it was to him that his brothers came. When they arrived,
        they bowed before him with their faces to the ground. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph recognized his brothers instantly, but he pretended to be
        a stranger and spoke harshly to them. \u201CWhere are you from?\u201D he
        demanded.\u201CFrom the land of Canaan,\u201D they replied. \u201CWe have
        come to buy food.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Although Joseph recognized his brothers, they didn\u2019t recognize
        him. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And he remembered the dreams he\u2019d had about them many years
        before. He said to them, \u201CYou are spies! You have come to see how vulnerable
        our land has become.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo, my lord!\u201D they exclaimed. \u201CYour servants have
        simply come to buy food. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We are all brothers\u2014members of the same family. We are honest
        men, sir! We are not spies!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes, you are!\u201D Joseph insisted. \u201CYou have come to
        see how vulnerable our land has become.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSir,\u201D they said, \u201Cthere are actually twelve of us.
        We, your servants, are all brothers, sons of a man living in the land of
        Canaan. Our youngest brother is back there with our father right now, and
        one of our brothers is no longer with us.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Joseph insisted, \u201CAs I said, you are spies! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is how I will test your story. I swear by the life of Pharaoh
        that you will never leave Egypt unless your youngest brother comes here! '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "One of you must go and get your brother. I\u2019ll keep the rest
        of you here in prison. Then we\u2019ll find out whether or not your story
        is true. By the life of Pharaoh, if it turns out that you don\u2019t have
        a younger brother, then I\u2019ll know you are spies.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joseph put them all in prison for three days. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "On the third day Joseph said to them, \u201CI am a God-fearing man.
        If you do as I say, you will live. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you really are honest men, choose one of your brothers to remain
        in prison. The rest of you may go home with grain for your starving families. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But you must bring your youngest brother back to me. This will prove
        that you are telling the truth, and you will not die.\u201D To this they
        agreed.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Speaking among themselves, they said, \u201CClearly we are being
        punished because of what we did to Joseph long ago. We saw his anguish when
        he pleaded for his life, but we wouldn\u2019t listen. That\u2019s why we\u2019re
        in this trouble.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDidn\u2019t I tell you not to sin against the boy?\u201D Reuben
        asked. \u201CBut you wouldn\u2019t listen. And now we have to answer for
        his blood!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Of course, they didn\u2019t know that Joseph understood them, for
        he had been speaking to them through an interpreter. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Now he turned away from them and began to weep. When he regained
        his composure, he spoke to them again. Then he chose Simeon from among them
        and had him tied up right before their eyes.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph then ordered his servants to fill the men\u2019s sacks with
        grain, but he also gave secret instructions to return each brother\u2019s
        payment at the top of his sack. He also gave them supplies for their journey
        home. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the brothers loaded their donkeys with the grain and headed for
        home.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But when they stopped for the night and one of them opened his sack
        to get grain for his donkey, he found his money in the top of his sack. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLook!\u201D he exclaimed to his brothers. \u201CMy money has
        been returned; it\u2019s here in my sack!\u201D Then their hearts sank. Trembling,
        they said to each other, \u201CWhat has God done to us?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the brothers came to their father, Jacob, in the land of Canaan,
        they told him everything that had happened to them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe man who is governor of the land spoke very harshly to us,\u201D
        they told him. \u201CHe accused us of being spies scouting the land. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But we said, \u2018We are honest men, not spies. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We are twelve brothers, sons of one father. One brother is no longer
        with us, and the youngest is at home with our father in the land of Canaan.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen the man who is governor of the land told us, \u2018This
        is how I will find out if you are honest men. Leave one of your brothers
        here with me, and take grain for your starving families and go on home. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But you must bring your youngest brother back to me. Then I will
        know you are honest men and not spies. Then I will give you back your brother,
        and you may trade freely in the land.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As they emptied out their sacks, there in each man\u2019s sack was
        the bag of money he had paid for the grain! The brothers and their father
        were terrified when they saw the bags of money. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob exclaimed, \u201CYou are robbing me of my children! Joseph
        is gone! Simeon is gone! And now you want to take Benjamin, too. Everything
        is going against me!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Reuben said to his father, \u201CYou may kill my two sons if
        I don\u2019t bring Benjamin back to you. I\u2019ll be responsible for him,
        and I promise to bring him back.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: The Brothers Return to Egypt
      content: '  But the famine continued to ravage the land of Canaan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the grain they had brought from Egypt was almost gone, Jacob
        said to his sons, \u201CGo back and buy us a little more food.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Judah said, \u201CThe man was serious when he warned us, \u2018You
        won\u2019t see my face again unless your brother is with you.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If you send Benjamin with us, we will go down and buy more food. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But if you don\u2019t let Benjamin go, we won\u2019t go either. Remember,
        the man said, \u2018You won\u2019t see my face again unless your brother
        is with you.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhy were you so cruel to me?\u201D Jacob[[COMMENT(0)]] moaned.
        \u201CWhy did you tell him you had another brother?\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '43:6 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Israel; </b>also in 43:11. See note on 35:21.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThe man kept asking us questions about our family,\u201D they
        replied. \u201CHe asked, \u2018Is your father still alive? Do you have another
        brother?\u2019 So we answered his questions. How could we know he would say,
        \u2018Bring your brother down here\u2019?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Judah said to his father, \u201CSend the boy with me, and we will
        be on our way. Otherwise we will all die of starvation\u2014and not only
        we, but you and our little ones. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I personally guarantee his safety. You may hold me responsible if
        I don\u2019t bring him back to you. Then let me bear the blame forever. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If we hadn\u2019t wasted all this time, we could have gone and returned
        twice by now.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So their father, Jacob, finally said to them, \u201CIf it can\u2019t
        be avoided, then at least do this. Pack your bags with the best products
        of this land. Take them down to the man as gifts\u2014balm, honey, gum, aromatic
        resin, pistachio nuts, and almonds. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Also take double the money that was put back in your sacks, as it
        was probably someone\u2019s mistake. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then take your brother, and go back to the man. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "May God Almighty[[COMMENT(0)]] give you mercy as you go before the
        man, so that he will release Simeon and let Benjamin return. But if I must
        lose my children, so be it.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '43:14 '
        content: Hebrew <b>El-Shaddai.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "So the men packed Jacob\u2019s gifts and double the money and headed
        off with Benjamin. They finally arrived in Egypt and presented themselves
        to Joseph. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Joseph saw Benjamin with them, he said to the manager of his
        household, \u201CThese men will eat with me this noon. Take them inside the
        palace. Then go slaughter an animal, and prepare a big feast.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So the man did as Joseph told him and took them into Joseph\u2019s
        palace.  "
      comments: []
    - title: "A Feast at Joseph\u2019s Palace"
      content: "The brothers were terrified when they saw that they were being taken
        into Joseph\u2019s house. \u201CIt\u2019s because of the money someone put
        in our sacks last time we were here,\u201D they said. \u201CHe plans to pretend
        that we stole it. Then he will seize us, make us slaves, and take our donkeys.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The brothers approached the manager of Joseph\u2019s household and
        spoke to him at the entrance to the palace. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSir,\u201D they said, \u201Cwe came to Egypt once before to
        buy food. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But as we were returning home, we stopped for the night and opened
        our sacks. Then we discovered that each man\u2019s money\u2014the exact amount
        paid\u2014was in the top of his sack! Here it is; we have brought it back
        with us. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We also have additional money to buy more food. We have no idea who
        put our money in our sacks.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CRelax. Don\u2019t be afraid,\u201D the household manager told
        them. \u201CYour God, the God of your father, must have put this treasure
        into your sacks. I know I received your payment.\u201D Then he released Simeon
        and brought him out to them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The manager then led the men into Joseph\u2019s palace. He gave them
        water to wash their feet and provided food for their donkeys. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They were told they would be eating there, so they prepared their
        gifts for Joseph\u2019s arrival at noon.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When Joseph came home, they gave him the gifts they had brought him,
        then bowed low to the ground before him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After greeting them, he asked, \u201CHow is your father, the old
        man you spoke about? Is he still alive?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes,\u201D they replied. \u201COur father, your servant, is
        alive and well.\u201D And they bowed low again.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joseph looked at his brother Benjamin, the son of his own mother.
        \u201CIs this your youngest brother, the one you told me about?\u201D Joseph
        asked. \u201CMay God be gracious to you, my son.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joseph hurried from the room because he was overcome with emotion
        for his brother. He went into his private room, where he broke down and wept. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After washing his face, he came back out, keeping himself under control.
        Then he ordered, \u201CBring out the food!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The waiters served Joseph at his own table, and his brothers were
        served at a separate table. The Egyptians who ate with Joseph sat at their
        own table, because Egyptians despise Hebrews and refuse to eat with them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joseph told each of his brothers where to sit, and to their amazement,
        he seated them according to age, from oldest to youngest. '
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Joseph\u2019s Silver Cup"
      content: "  When his brothers were ready to leave, Joseph gave these instructions
        to his palace manager: \u201CFill each of their sacks with as much grain
        as they can carry, and put each man\u2019s money back into his sack. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then put my personal silver cup at the top of the youngest brother\u2019s
        sack, along with the money for his grain.\u201D So the manager did as Joseph
        instructed him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The brothers were up at dawn and were sent on their journey with
        their loaded donkeys. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when they had gone only a short distance and were barely out
        of the city, Joseph said to his palace manager, \u201CChase after them and
        stop them. When you catch up with them, ask them, \u2018Why have you repaid
        my kindness with such evil? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why have you stolen my master\u2019s silver cup,[[COMMENT(0)]] which
        he uses to predict the future? What a wicked thing you have done!\u2019\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '44:5 '
        content: As in Greek version; Hebrew lacks this phrase.
    - title: 
      content: 'When the palace manager caught up with the men, he spoke to them
        as he had been instructed.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat are you talking about?\u201D the brothers responded. \u201CWe
        are your servants and would never do such a thing! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Didn\u2019t we return the money we found in our sacks? We brought
        it back all the way from the land of Canaan. Why would we steal silver or
        gold from your master\u2019s house? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "If you find his cup with any one of us, let that man die. And all
        the rest of us, my lord, will be your slaves.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThat\u2019s fair,\u201D the man replied. \u201CBut only the
        one who stole the cup will be my slave. The rest of you may go free.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'They all quickly took their sacks from the backs of their donkeys
        and opened them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The palace manager searched the brothers\u2019 sacks, from the oldest
        to the youngest. And the cup was found in Benjamin\u2019s sack! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'When the brothers saw this, they tore their clothing in despair.
        Then they loaded their donkeys again and returned to the city.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joseph was still in his palace when Judah and his brothers arrived,
        and they fell to the ground before him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CWhat have you done?\u201D Joseph demanded. \u201CDon\u2019t
        you know that a man like me can predict the future?\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Judah answered, \u201COh, my lord, what can we say to you? How can
        we explain this? How can we prove our innocence? God is punishing us for
        our sins. My lord, we have all returned to be your slaves\u2014all of us,
        not just our brother who had your cup in his sack.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: Judah Speaks for His Brothers
      content: "\u201CNo,\u201D Joseph said. \u201CI would never do such a thing!
        Only the man who stole the cup will be my slave. The rest of you may go back
        to your father in peace.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Judah stepped forward and said, \u201CPlease, my lord, let your
        servant say just one word to you. Please, do not be angry with me, even though
        you are as powerful as Pharaoh himself.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CMy lord, previously you asked us, your servants, \u2018Do you
        have a father or a brother?\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And we responded, \u2018Yes, my lord, we have a father who is an
        old man, and his youngest son is a child of his old age. His full brother
        is dead, and he alone is left of his mother\u2019s children, and his father
        loves him very much.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd you said to us, \u2018Bring him here so I can see him with
        my own eyes.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But we said to you, \u2018My lord, the boy cannot leave his father,
        for his father would die.\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But you told us, \u2018Unless your youngest brother comes with you,
        you will never see my face again.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo we returned to your servant, our father, and told him what
        you had said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Later, when he said, \u2018Go back again and buy us more food,\u2019 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "we replied, \u2018We can\u2019t go unless you let our youngest brother
        go with us. We\u2019ll never get to see the man\u2019s face unless our youngest
        brother is with us.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CThen my father said to us, \u2018As you know, my wife had two
        sons, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'and one of them went away and never returned. Doubtless he was torn
        to pieces by some wild animal. I have never seen him since. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Now if you take his brother away from me, and any harm comes to him,
        you will send this grieving, white-haired man to his grave.[[COMMENT(0)]]\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '44:29 '
        content: Hebrew <b>to Sheol; </b>also in 44:31.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAnd now, my lord, I cannot go back to my father without the
        boy. Our father\u2019s life is bound up in the boy\u2019s life. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'If he sees that the boy is not with us, our father will die. We,
        your servants, will indeed be responsible for sending that grieving, white-haired
        man to his grave. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "My lord, I guaranteed to my father that I would take care of the
        boy. I told him, \u2018If I don\u2019t bring him back to you, I will bear
        the blame forever.\u2019  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSo please, my lord, let me stay here as a slave instead of
        the boy, and let the boy return with his brothers. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Joseph Reveals His Identity
      content: "  Joseph could stand it no longer. There were many people in the
        room, and he said to his attendants, \u201COut, all of you!\u201D So he was
        alone with his brothers when he told them who he was. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he broke down and wept. He wept so loudly the Egyptians could
        hear him, and word of it quickly carried to Pharaoh\u2019s palace.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am Joseph!\u201D he said to his brothers. \u201CIs my father
        still alive?\u201D But his brothers were speechless! They were stunned to
        realize that Joseph was standing there in front of them. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CPlease, come closer,\u201D he said to them. So they came closer.
        And he said again, \u201CI am Joseph, your brother, whom you sold into slavery
        in Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But don\u2019t be upset, and don\u2019t be angry with yourselves
        for selling me to this place. It was God who sent me here ahead of you to
        preserve your lives. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This famine that has ravaged the land for two years will last five
        more years, and there will be neither plowing nor harvesting. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'God has sent me ahead of you to keep you and your families alive
        and to preserve many survivors.[[COMMENT(0)]]  '
      comments:
      - number: '45:7 '
        content: Or <b>and to save you with an extraordinary rescue. </b>The meaning
          of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: "So it was God who sent me here, not you! And he is the one who made
        me an adviser[[COMMENT(0)]] to Pharaoh\u2014the manager of his entire palace
        and the governor of all Egypt.  "
      comments:
      - number: '45:8 '
        content: Hebrew <b>a father.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow hurry back to my father and tell him, \u2018This is what
        your son Joseph says: God has made me master over all the land of Egypt.
        So come down to me immediately! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You can live in the region of Goshen, where you can be near me with
        all your children and grandchildren, your flocks and herds, and everything
        you own. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "I will take care of you there, for there are still five years of
        famine ahead of us. Otherwise you, your household, and all your animals will
        starve.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joseph added, \u201CLook! You can see for yourselves, and so
        can my brother Benjamin, that I really am Joseph! "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Go tell my father of my honored position here in Egypt. Describe
        for him everything you have seen, and then bring my father here quickly.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Weeping with joy, he embraced Benjamin, and Benjamin did the same. '
      comments: []
    - title: Pharaoh Invites Jacob to Egypt
      content: 'Then Joseph kissed each of his brothers and wept over them, and after
        that they began talking freely with him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The news soon reached Pharaoh\u2019s palace: \u201CJoseph\u2019s
        brothers have arrived!\u201D Pharaoh and his officials were all delighted
        to hear this.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CTell your brothers, \u2018This is what
        you must do: Load your pack animals, and hurry back to the land of Canaan. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then get your father and all of your families, and return here to
        me. I will give you the very best land in Egypt, and you will eat from the
        best that the land produces.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CTell your brothers, \u2018Take
        wagons from the land of Egypt to carry your little children and your wives,
        and bring your father here. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Don\u2019t worry about your personal belongings, for the best of
        all the land of Egypt is yours.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So the sons of Jacob[[COMMENT(0)]] did as they were told. Joseph
        provided them with wagons, as Pharaoh had commanded, and he gave them supplies
        for the journey. '
      comments:
      - number: '45:21 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Israel; </b>also in 45:28. See note on 35:21.
    - title: 
      content: "And he gave each of them new clothes\u2014but to Benjamin he gave
        five changes of clothes and 300 pieces[[COMMENT(0)]] of silver. "
      comments:
      - number: '45:22 '
        content: Hebrew <b>300 [shekels], </b>about 7.5 pounds or 3.4 kilograms in
          weight.
    - title: 
      content: 'He also sent his father ten male donkeys loaded with the finest products
        of Egypt, and ten female donkeys loaded with grain and bread and other supplies
        he would need on his journey.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joseph sent his brothers off, and as they left, he called after
        them, \u201CDon\u2019t quarrel about all this along the way!\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'And they left Egypt and returned to their father, Jacob, in the land
        of Canaan.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CJoseph is still alive!\u201D they told him. \u201CAnd he is
        governor of all the land of Egypt!\u201D Jacob was stunned at the news\u2014he
        couldn\u2019t believe it. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But when they repeated to Jacob everything Joseph had told them,
        and when he saw the wagons Joseph had sent to carry him, their father\u2019s
        spirits revived.  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Journey to Egypt"
      content: '  So Jacob[[COMMENT(0)]] set out for Egypt with all his possessions.
        And when he came to Beersheba, he offered sacrifices to the God of his father,
        Isaac. '
      comments:
      - number: '46:1 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Israel; </b>also in 46:29, 30. See note on 35:21.
    - title: 
      content: "During the night God spoke to him in a vision. \u201CJacob! Jacob!\u201D
        he called.\u201CHere I am,\u201D Jacob replied.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CI am God,[[COMMENT(0)]] the God of your father,\u201D the voice
        said. \u201CDo not be afraid to go down to Egypt, for there I will make your
        family into a great nation. "
      comments:
      - number: '46:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>I am El.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "I will go with you down to Egypt, and I will bring you back again.
        You will die in Egypt, but Joseph will be with you to close your eyes.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Jacob left Beersheba, and his sons took him to Egypt. They carried
        him and their little ones and their wives in the wagons Pharaoh had provided
        for them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "They also took all their livestock and all the personal belongings
        they had acquired in the land of Canaan. So Jacob and his entire family went
        to Egypt\u2014 "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "sons and grandsons, daughters and granddaughters\u2014all his descendants.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These are the names of the descendants of Israel\u2014the sons of
        Jacob\u2014who went to Egypt:Reuben was Jacob\u2019s oldest son. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Reuben were Hanoch, Pallu, Hezron, and Carmi.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The sons of Simeon were Jemuel, Jamin, Ohad, Jakin, Zohar, and Shaul.
        (Shaul\u2019s mother was a Canaanite woman.)  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Levi were Gershon, Kohath, and Merari.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Judah were Er, Onan, Shelah, Perez, and Zerah (though
        Er and Onan had died in the land of Canaan). The sons of Perez were Hezron
        and Hamul.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Issachar were Tola, Puah,[[COMMENT(0)]] Jashub,[[COMMENT(1)]]
        and Shimron.  '
      comments:
      - number: '46:13a '
        content: As in Syriac version and Samaritan Pentateuch (see also 1 Chr 7:1);
          Hebrew reads <b>Puvah.</b>
      - number: '46:13b '
        content: As in some Greek manuscripts and Samaritan Pentateuch (see also
          Num 26:24; 1 Chr 7:1); Hebrew reads <b>Iob.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Zebulun were Sered, Elon, and Jahleel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the sons of Leah and Jacob who were born in Paddan-aram,
        in addition to their daughter, Dinah. The number of Jacob\u2019s descendants
        (male and female) through Leah was thirty-three.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Gad were Zephon,[[COMMENT(0)]] Haggi, Shuni, Ezbon, Eri,
        Arodi, and Areli.  '
      comments:
      - number: '46:16 '
        content: As in Greek version and Samaritan Pentateuch (see also Num 26:15);
          Hebrew reads <b>Ziphion.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "The sons of Asher were Imnah, Ishvah, Ishvi, and Beriah. Their sister
        was Serah. Beriah\u2019s sons were Heber and Malkiel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the sons of Zilpah, the servant given to Leah by her father,
        Laban. The number of Jacob\u2019s descendants through Zilpah was sixteen.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The sons of Jacob\u2019s wife Rachel were Joseph and Benjamin.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph\u2019s sons, born in the land of Egypt, were Manasseh and
        Ephraim. Their mother was Asenath, daughter of Potiphera, the priest of On.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '46:20 '
        content: Greek version reads <b>of Heliopolis.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "Benjamin\u2019s sons were Bela, Beker, Ashbel, Gera, Naaman, Ehi,
        Rosh, Muppim, Huppim, and Ard.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the sons of Rachel and Jacob. The number of Jacob\u2019s
        descendants through Rachel was fourteen.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The son of Dan was Hushim.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'The sons of Naphtali were Jahzeel, Guni, Jezer, and Shillem.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These were the sons of Bilhah, the servant given to Rachel by her
        father, Laban. The number of Jacob\u2019s descendants through Bilhah was
        seven.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The total number of Jacob\u2019s direct descendants who went with
        him to Egypt, not counting his sons\u2019 wives, was sixty-six. "
      comments: []
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Family Arrives in Goshen"
      content: "In addition, Joseph had two sons[[COMMENT(0)]] who were born in Egypt.
        So altogether, there were seventy[[COMMENT(1)]] members of Jacob\u2019s family
        in the land of Egypt.  "
      comments:
      - number: '46:27a '
        content: "Greek version reads <b>nine sons, </b>probably including Joseph\u2019s
          grandsons through Ephraim and Manasseh (see 1 Chr 7:14-20)."
      - number: '46:27b '
        content: Greek version reads <b>seventy-five; </b>see note on Exod 1:5.
    - title: 
      content: 'As they neared their destination, Jacob sent Judah ahead to meet
        Joseph and get directions to the region of Goshen. And when they finally
        arrived there, '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joseph prepared his chariot and traveled to Goshen to meet his father,
        Jacob. When Joseph arrived, he embraced his father and wept, holding him
        for a long time. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Finally, Jacob said to Joseph, \u201CNow I am ready to die, since
        I have seen your face again and know you are still alive.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Joseph said to his brothers and to his father\u2019s entire family,
        \u201CI will go to Pharaoh and tell him, \u2018My brothers and my father\u2019s
        entire family have come to me from the land of Canaan. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "These men are shepherds, and they raise livestock. They have brought
        with them their flocks and herds and everything they own.\u2019\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he said, \u201CWhen Pharaoh calls for you and asks you about
        your occupation, "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Jacob Blesses Pharaoh
      content: "  Then Joseph went to see Pharaoh and told him, \u201CMy father and
        my brothers have arrived from the land of Canaan. They have come with all
        their flocks and herds and possessions, and they are now in the region of
        Goshen.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joseph took five of his brothers with him and presented them to Pharaoh. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "And Pharaoh asked the brothers, \u201CWhat is your occupation?\u201DThey
        replied, \u201CWe, your servants, are shepherds, just like our ancestors. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "We have come to live here in Egypt for a while, for there is no pasture
        for our flocks in Canaan. The famine is very severe there. So please, we
        request permission to live in the region of Goshen.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Pharaoh said to Joseph, \u201CNow that your father and brothers
        have joined you here, "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "choose any place in the entire land of Egypt for them to live. Give
        them the best land of Egypt. Let them live in the region of Goshen. And if
        any of them have special skills, put them in charge of my livestock, too.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Joseph brought in his father, Jacob, and presented him to Pharaoh.
        And Jacob blessed Pharaoh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CHow old are you?\u201D Pharaoh asked him.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob replied, \u201CI have traveled this earth for 130 hard years.
        But my life has been short compared to the lives of my ancestors.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Then Jacob blessed Pharaoh again before leaving his court.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joseph assigned the best land of Egypt\u2014the region of Rameses\u2014to
        his father and his brothers, and he settled them there, just as Pharaoh had
        commanded. "
      comments: []
    - title: "Joseph\u2019s Leadership in the Famine"
      content: 'And Joseph provided food for his father and his brothers in amounts
        appropriate to the number of their dependents, including the smallest children.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, the famine became so severe that all the food was used
        up, and people were starving throughout the lands of Egypt and Canaan. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "By selling grain to the people, Joseph eventually collected all the
        money in Egypt and Canaan, and he put the money in Pharaoh\u2019s treasury. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the people of Egypt and Canaan ran out of money, all the Egyptians
        came to Joseph. \u201COur money is gone!\u201D they cried. \u201CBut please
        give us food, or we will die before your very eyes!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph replied, \u201CSince your money is gone, bring me your livestock.
        I will give you food in exchange for your livestock.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So they brought their livestock to Joseph in exchange for food. In
        exchange for their horses, flocks of sheep and goats, herds of cattle, and
        donkeys, Joseph provided them with food for another year.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But that year ended, and the next year they came again and said,
        \u201CWe cannot hide the truth from you, my lord. Our money is gone, and
        all our livestock and cattle are yours. We have nothing left to give but
        our bodies and our land. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Why should we die before your very eyes? Buy us and our land in exchange
        for food; we offer our land and ourselves as slaves for Pharaoh. Just give
        us grain so we may live and not die, and so the land does not become empty
        and desolate.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joseph bought all the land of Egypt for Pharaoh. All the Egyptians
        sold him their fields because the famine was so severe, and soon all the
        land belonged to Pharaoh. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'As for the people, he made them all slaves,[[COMMENT(0)]] from one
        end of Egypt to the other. '
      comments:
      - number: '47:21 '
        content: As in Greek version and Samaritan Pentateuch; Hebrew reads <b>he
          moved them all into the towns.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "The only land he did not buy was the land belonging to the priests.
        They received an allotment of food directly from Pharaoh, so they didn\u2019t
        need to sell their land.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joseph said to the people, \u201CLook, today I have bought you
        and your land for Pharaoh. I will provide you with seed so you can plant
        the fields. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then when you harvest it, one-fifth of your crop will belong to Pharaoh.
        You may keep the remaining four-fifths as seed for your fields and as food
        for you, your households, and your little ones.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYou have saved our lives!\u201D they exclaimed. \u201CMay it
        please you, my lord, to let us be Pharaoh\u2019s servants.\u201D "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joseph then issued a decree still in effect in the land of Egypt,
        that Pharaoh should receive one-fifth of all the crops grown on his land.
        Only the land belonging to the priests was not given to Pharaoh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Meanwhile, the people of Israel settled in the region of Goshen in
        Egypt. There they acquired property, and they were fruitful, and their population
        grew rapidly. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jacob lived for seventeen years after his arrival in Egypt, so he
        lived 147 years in all.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "As the time of his death drew near, Jacob[[COMMENT(0)]] called for
        his son Joseph and said to him, \u201CPlease do me this favor. Put your hand
        under my thigh and swear that you will treat me with unfailing love by honoring
        this last request: Do not bury me in Egypt. "
      comments:
      - number: '47:29 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Israel; </b>also in 47:31b. See note on 35:21.
    - title: 
      content: "When I die, please take my body out of Egypt and bury me with my
        ancestors.\u201DSo Joseph promised, \u201CI will do as you ask.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: Jacob Blesses Manasseh and Ephraim
      content: "  One day not long after this, word came to Joseph, \u201CYour father
        is failing rapidly.\u201D So Joseph went to visit his father, and he took
        with him his two sons, Manasseh and Ephraim.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When Joseph arrived, Jacob was told, \u201CYour son Joseph has come
        to see you.\u201D So Jacob[[COMMENT(0)]] gathered his strength and sat up
        in his bed.  "
      comments:
      - number: '48:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Israel; </b>also in 48:8, 10, 11, 13, 14, 21. See note
          on 35:21.
    - title: 
      content: "Jacob said to Joseph, \u201CGod Almighty[[COMMENT(0)]] appeared to
        me at Luz in the land of Canaan and blessed me. "
      comments:
      - number: '48:3 '
        content: Hebrew <b>El-Shaddai.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "He said to me, \u2018I will make you fruitful, and I will multiply
        your descendants. I will make you a multitude of nations. And I will give
        this land of Canaan to your descendants[[COMMENT(0)]] after you as an everlasting
        possession.\u2019  "
      comments:
      - number: '48:4 '
        content: Hebrew <b>seed; </b>also in 48:19.
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNow I am claiming as my own sons these two boys of yours, Ephraim
        and Manasseh, who were born here in the land of Egypt before I arrived. They
        will be my sons, just as Reuben and Simeon are. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But any children born to you in the future will be your own, and
        they will inherit land within the territories of their brothers Ephraim and
        Manasseh.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CLong ago, as I was returning from Paddan-aram,[[COMMENT(0)]]
        Rachel died in the land of Canaan. We were still on the way, some distance
        from Ephrath (that is, Bethlehem). So with great sorrow I buried her there
        beside the road to Ephrath.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '48:7 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Paddan, </b>referring to Paddan-aram; compare Gen 35:9.
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob looked over at the two boys. \u201CAre these your sons?\u201D
        he asked.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CYes,\u201D Joseph told him, \u201Cthese are the sons God has
        given me here in Egypt.\u201DAnd Jacob said, \u201CBring them closer to me,
        so I can bless them.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Jacob was half blind because of his age and could hardly see. So
        Joseph brought the boys close to him, and Jacob kissed and embraced them. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob said to Joseph, \u201CI never thought I would see your
        face again, but now God has let me see your children, too!\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Joseph moved the boys, who were at their grandfather\u2019s knees,
        and he bowed with his face to the ground. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he positioned the boys in front of Jacob. With his right hand
        he directed Ephraim toward Jacob\u2019s left hand, and with his left hand
        he put Manasseh at Jacob\u2019s right hand. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Jacob crossed his arms as he reached out to lay his hands on
        the boys\u2019 heads. He put his right hand on the head of Ephraim, though
        he was the younger boy, and his left hand on the head of Manasseh, though
        he was the firstborn. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then he blessed Joseph and said,\u201CMay the God before whom my
        grandfather Abrahamand my father, Isaac, walked\u2014the God who has been
        my shepherdall my life, to this very day,  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "the Angel who has redeemed me from all harm\u2014may he bless these
        boys.May they preserve my nameand the names of Abraham and Isaac.And may
        their descendants multiply greatlythroughout the earth.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Joseph was upset when he saw that his father placed his right
        hand on Ephraim\u2019s head. So Joseph lifted it to move it from Ephraim\u2019s
        head to Manasseh\u2019s head. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNo, my father,\u201D he said. \u201CThis one is the firstborn.
        Put your right hand on his head.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But his father refused. \u201CI know, my son; I know,\u201D he replied.
        \u201CManasseh will also become a great people, but his younger brother will
        become even greater. And his descendants will become a multitude of nations.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Jacob blessed the boys that day with this blessing: \u201CThe
        people of Israel will use your names when they give a blessing. They will
        say, \u2018May God make you as prosperous as Ephraim and Manasseh.\u2019\u201D
        In this way, Jacob put Ephraim ahead of Manasseh.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob said to Joseph, \u201CLook, I am about to die, but God
        will be with you and will take you back to Canaan, the land of your ancestors. "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Last Words to His Sons"
      content: "  Then Jacob called together all his sons and said, \u201CGather
        around me, and I will tell you what will happen to each of you in the days
        to come.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CCome and listen, you sons of Jacob;listen to Israel, your father.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CReuben, you are my firstborn, my strength,the child of my vigorous
        youth.You are first in rank and first in power.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But you are as unruly as a flood,and you will be first no longer.For
        you went to bed with my wife;you defiled my marriage couch.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSimeon and Levi are two of a kind;their weapons are instruments
        of violence.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'May I never join in their meetings;may I never be a party to their
        plans.For in their anger they murdered men,and they crippled oxen just for
        sport.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A curse on their anger, for it is fierce;a curse on their wrath,
        for it is cruel.I will scatter them among the descendants of Jacob;I will
        disperse them throughout Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CJudah, your brothers will praise you.You will grasp your enemies
        by the neck.All your relatives will bow before you.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Judah, my son, is a young lionthat has finished eating its prey.Like
        a lion he crouches and lies down;like a lioness\u2014who dares to rouse him?  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The scepter will not depart from Judah,nor the ruler\u2019s staff
        from his descendants,[[COMMENT(0)]]until the coming of the one to whom it
        belongs,[[COMMENT(1)]]the one whom all nations will honor.  "
      comments:
      - number: '49:10a '
        content: Hebrew <b>from between his feet.</b>
      - number: '49:10b '
        content: Or <b>until tribute is brought to him and the peoples obey; </b>traditionally
          rendered <b>until Shiloh comes.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'He ties his foal to a grapevine,the colt of his donkey to a choice
        vine.He washes his clothes in wine,his robes in the blood of grapes.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'His eyes are darker than wine,and his teeth are whiter than milk.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CZebulun will settle by the seashoreand will be a harbor for
        ships;his borders will extend to Sidon.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CIssachar is a sturdy donkey,resting between two saddlepacks.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '49:14 '
        content: Or <b>sheepfolds, </b>or <b>hearths.</b>
    - title: 
      content: 'When he sees how good the countryside isand how pleasant the land,he
        will bend his shoulder to the loadand submit himself to hard labor.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CDan will govern his people,like any other tribe in Israel.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Dan will be a snake beside the road,a poisonous viper along the paththat
        bites the horse\u2019s hoovesso its rider is thrown off.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'I trust in you for salvation, O <smallcaps>Lord</smallcaps>!  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CGad will be attacked by marauding bands,but he will attack
        them when they retreat.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CAsher will dine on rich foodsand produce food fit for kings.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CNaphtali is a doe set freethat bears beautiful fawns.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CJoseph is the foal of a wild donkey,the foal of a wild donkey
        at a spring\u2014one of the wild donkeys on the ridge.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '49:22 '
        content: Or <b>Joseph is a fruitful tree, / a fruitful tree beside a spring.
          / His branches reach over the wall. </b>The meaning of the Hebrew is uncertain.
    - title: 
      content: 'Archers attacked him savagely;they shot at him and harassed him.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'But his bow remained taut,and his arms were strengthenedby the hands
        of the Mighty One of Jacob,by the Shepherd, the Rock of Israel.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'May the God of your father help you;may the Almighty bless youwith
        the blessings of the heavens above,and blessings of the watery depths below,and
        blessings of the breasts and womb.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'May my fatherly blessings on yousurpass the blessings of my ancestors,[[COMMENT(0)]]reaching
        to the heights of the eternal hills.May these blessings rest on the head
        of Joseph,who is a prince among his brothers.  '
      comments:
      - number: '49:26 '
        content: Or <b>of the ancient mountains.</b>
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CBenjamin is a ravenous wolf,devouring his enemies in the morningand
        dividing his plunder in the evening.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: "Jacob\u2019s Death and Burial"
      content: 'These are the twelve tribes of Israel, and this is what their father
        said as he told his sons good-bye. He blessed each one with an appropriate
        message.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Jacob instructed them, \u201CSoon I will die and join my ancestors.
        Bury me with my father and grandfather in the cave in the field of Ephron
        the Hittite. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'This is the cave in the field of Machpelah, near Mamre in Canaan,
        that Abraham bought from Ephron the Hittite as a permanent burial site. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'There Abraham and his wife Sarah are buried. There Isaac and his
        wife, Rebekah, are buried. And there I buried Leah. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "It is the plot of land and the cave that my grandfather Abraham bought
        from the Hittites.\u201D  "
      comments: []
  - verses:
    - title: 
      content: '  Joseph threw himself on his father and wept over him and kissed
        him. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joseph told the physicians who served him to embalm his father\u2019s
        body; so Jacob[[COMMENT(0)]] was embalmed. "
      comments:
      - number: '50:2 '
        content: Hebrew <b>Israel. </b>See note on 35:21.
    - title: 
      content: 'The embalming process took the usual forty days. And the Egyptians
        mourned his death for seventy days.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When the period of mourning was over, Joseph approached Pharaoh\u2019s
        advisers and said, \u201CPlease do me this favor and speak to Pharaoh on
        my behalf. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Tell him that my father made me swear an oath. He said to me, \u2018Listen,
        I am about to die. Take my body back to the land of Canaan, and bury me in
        the tomb I prepared for myself.\u2019 So please allow me to go and bury my
        father. After his burial, I will return without delay.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Pharaoh agreed to Joseph\u2019s request. \u201CGo and bury your father,
        as he made you promise,\u201D he said. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So Joseph went up to bury his father. He was accompanied by all of
        Pharaoh\u2019s officials, all the senior members of Pharaoh\u2019s household,
        and all the senior officers of Egypt. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'Joseph also took his entire household and his brothers and their
        households. But they left their little children and flocks and herds in the
        land of Goshen. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'A great number of chariots and charioteers accompanied Joseph.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "When they arrived at the threshing floor of Atad, near the Jordan
        River, they held a very great and solemn memorial service, with a seven-day
        period of mourning for Joseph\u2019s father. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "The local residents, the Canaanites, watched them mourning at the
        threshing floor of Atad. Then they renamed that place (which is near the
        Jordan) Abel-mizraim,[[COMMENT(0)]] for they said, \u201CThis is a place
        of deep mourning for these Egyptians.\u201D  "
      comments:
      - number: '50:11 '
        content: "<b>Abel-mizraim </b>means \u201Cmourning of the Egyptians.\u201D"
    - title: 
      content: "So Jacob\u2019s sons did as he had commanded them. "
      comments: []
    - title: Joseph Reassures His Brothers
      content: 'They carried his body to the land of Canaan and buried him in the
        cave in the field of Machpelah, near Mamre. This is the cave that Abraham
        had bought as a permanent burial site from Ephron the Hittite.  '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "After burying Jacob, Joseph returned to Egypt with his brothers and
        all who had accompanied him to his father\u2019s burial. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But now that their father was dead, Joseph\u2019s brothers became
        fearful. \u201CNow Joseph will show his anger and pay us back for all the
        wrong we did to him,\u201D they said.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "So they sent this message to Joseph: \u201CBefore your father died,
        he instructed us "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "to say to you: \u2018Please forgive your brothers for the great wrong
        they did to you\u2014for their sin in treating you so cruelly.\u2019 So we,
        the servants of the God of your father, beg you to forgive our sin.\u201D
        When Joseph received the message, he broke down and wept. "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then his brothers came and threw themselves down before Joseph. \u201CLook,
        we are your slaves!\u201D they said.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "But Joseph replied, \u201CDon\u2019t be afraid of me. Am I God, that
        I can punish you? "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'You intended to harm me, but God intended it all for good. He brought
        me to this position so I could save the lives of many people. '
      comments: []
    - title: The Death of Joseph
      content: "No, don\u2019t be afraid. I will continue to take care of you and
        your children.\u201D So he reassured them by speaking kindly to them.  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: 'So Joseph and his brothers and their families continued to live in
        Egypt. Joseph lived to the age of 110. '
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "He lived to see three generations of descendants of his son Ephraim,
        and he lived to see the birth of the children of Manasseh\u2019s son Makir,
        whom he claimed as his own.[[COMMENT(0)]]  "
      comments:
      - number: '50:23 '
        content: "Hebrew <b>who were born on Joseph\u2019s knees.</b>"
    - title: 
      content: "\u201CSoon I will die,\u201D Joseph told his brothers, \u201Cbut
        God will surely come to help you and lead you out of this land of Egypt.
        He will bring you back to the land he solemnly promised to give to Abraham,
        to Isaac, and to Jacob.\u201D  "
      comments: []
    - title: 
      content: "Then Joseph made the sons of Israel swear an oath, and he said, \u201CWhen
        God comes to help you and lead you back, you must take my bones with you.\u201D "
      comments: []
